animal.description:
Someone else's loss could be your forever treasure chest full of gentleness, amiability, intelligence, and loyalty!  Toby's owner has had a rough year; he moved into an apartment that does not allow dogs.  We are looking for a permanent home for this loving boy.  Toby is about three years old and weighs 39.8 pounds give or take an ounce.  His birthdate is November 16, 2017.

His ideal day would include a routine that includes daily walks, patience, lots of love, and he will be forever grateful to a human who spends time with him.

Toby is a big fan of walking on the leash.

He can live with children who can easily direct his easy going but jovial nature in whatever direction they want him to follow. He is a handsome boy who will really appreciate a family big or small that provides that needed routine, shared exercise and training, and lots of hugs.

In the middle of the evening when the home is quiet, dogs have been walked, fed, and finished their business outside, he wants to join his humans and the other dogs on the sofa for quiet family time.

Although not without accidents, he tries his best to remember where to pee and poo. 

Application is online at karmicrescue.org

(!@#$%^&*()_!@#$%^&*()_!@#$%^&*()_!@#$%^&*()_!@#$%^&*()_!@#$%^&*

What breed is my dog? Please remember we do not complete DNA tests on our rescued pups. If we do not know who the mom or dad is for sure, we guess; we use Bing Visual Search. And, we look at their paws, ears, snout, coloring, and body build. So often, we are not spot on. Mutts are usually more healthy than not. And, remember too that even if you know the supposed dominant breed in your new puppy or adult dog, it does not mean that those particular genes will dominate your dog's personality.

animal.description:
Meet Django!
This sweet boy is a very special rescue to us. Our co-founder Karen had been watching his profile for days, if not weeks, and worked tirelessly to find him a foster family so that we could rescue him. Thanks to the generosity from the shelter we were able to buy Django a few extra days and keep him off the euthanasia list. Then a Christmas miracle occurred, and we had an amazing volunteer step up and offer to foster Django! Django is alive today thanks to a foster family who opened their home during the holidays. Without them Django would have faced euthanasia at the shelter. 
Now this boy is free and ready to find his forever home! Django is approximately 4-6 years old and weighs 63 lbs. His personality has really flourished since being out of the shelter environment and is showing his true loving and goofy personality. Django loves people and kids! This boy is the epitome of sweet and loving. He also loves a good cuddle session and is more of a couch potato than an outdoor enthusiast. Actually, you won’t catch him outside for very long at all unless it’s for a walk in the sunshine. He is well mannered in his foster home and has proven to be house trained and crate trained. He is just a few days out of the shelter so we have not introduced him to other dogs yet, but will update as soon as we know how he interacts with other pets!
To adopt Django fill out our adoption application online at 
www.bullluvablepaws.org/adopt

animal.description:
Dakota is a 6 year old, spayed female Black Mouth Cur (~60 pounds), microchipped, up to date on her shots, and very healthy. She's been with us since 2015. She's very affectionate with humans, but she would do best as the only dog in the home. She might be OK with compatible larger dogs (meeting suggested- she's OK with our 21 month German Shepard), but she has issues with our small dogs, which is why we made the difficult decision to rehome her. No cats- we don't have them, but she wants to chase them on sight. She's an energetic dog, and loves to run along with a bike, go on hikes or wander with you sniffing out the area (she'll handle the sniffing!). She does well on a leash, and rides well in the car. Even at 60 pounds, she's something of a lap dog, and will snuggle up under your chin. If that's not for you, she knows "off!" and will be happy with lots of head and chest scritches and belly rubs. She knows sit, down, stay (to a point), wait, roll over, high 5, crate, place, is fully housebroken, and is used to using a dog door, but will also scratch to be let out. She's food-driven, and easy to train with the offer of treats. She does well in a crate, for sleeping or for breaks during the day. Apart from grabbing the occasional sock, or food left unattended, she's very good around the house, and before the pandemic, we were able to leave her on her own with dog door access to the yard.  Please contact us to arrange a meeting- we're sure you'll love her.
Please Contact : Bob Musser
(916)213-4178

animal.description:
Look at me, look at me—my name is Sloane—don’t you just think I am the prettiest girl there ever was? If you think I am pretty, wait until you meet me, you will wonder how you managed to get along all your life without me :) I have lived in a home my entire life until I was surrendered to rescue. That was a glorious day because now I know I will one day soon go to live with an amazing family who will make me their everything. When I was in boarding I had lots of other dog friends and loved each of them—especially the ones who loved to play. My foster mama took me into the house where I got to meet the kitties who rubbed all over me—they are almost as special as me. People—boy do I LOVE people! I must warn you - I take my job seriously and like all good Pyrs have learned to bark to ward off bad things—like a flock of birds flying overhead. I have heard it said that I am smart—when I see a treat I know to sit and don’t even wait for the command! My foster mama says I walk around wagging my tail saying “I am so cute, aren’t I cute, look at me”. What can I say, I love to be the center of attention! I have a way of drawing you in to me! My PYRfect home would have either another resident dog or a dog who comes over to play a lot, a big yard with a locking gate, children (I lived with a small child), and a person(s) who will continue to teach me the wonders of life!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
This is Moonshine! He was born approximately February 2020, is a pit mix and is such a happy boy despite his sad past. He was found by a rural shelter with over 130 BB pellet wounds all over his body after being shot with a shotgun by a terrible human. He was so timid at first around humans but turns corners so quickly. Now he is in a foster home, his wounds are healing, and he is getting more confident by the day! He warms up rather fast and is doing amazing. This gentle boy loves other dogs and is great around children. He loves to give kisses and is the best cuddle buddy! He loves to chew, and is learning quickly to only chew on toys (and learning fast!). He is fixed, potty trained, and microchipped. But most of all, this sweet boy just wants to be loved, and has so much love to give in return!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.=========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
Princeton (Prince) is a sweet and energetic Doberman Pinscher guy--nearly 5 years old. He is affectionate, a little needy and playful. He likes to cuddle with his humans...he thinks he's a lap dog. 
He's a large (90 lbs.) strong dog so leash walking needs to be done with a no pull harness (leash attachment at the chest). He can be crated for short periods of time, but has been good when left alone loose in the house.
As is true for most of his breed, Prince is a great watch dog.  He has led a somewhat sheltered life, so needs someone who can help socialize him to be less distrusting of new people and dogs.  We think he is not the dog to share a home with a cat and he has no real experience with young children, so he will do best in a home with respectful children 8 or older or an all adult home.  He also will do best as the only dog in the home.  
Prince definitely needs a home with a fenced yard (not electric/invisible fence) and needs a person or family that doesn't need to regularly leave him alone long hours. 
(A $400 adoption fee is required.) 
If you are interested in this dog, please go to the Adopt page of our website where you will find a link to an adoption application form  https://www.chewdogrescue.org/index.php/component/rsform/form/5-adoption-application-form
 
If you have previously submitted an application form, there is no need to re-apply. Just let us know you're interested in this dog. We do our best to match families and dogs so everyone is pleased and the placement is permanent. We reserve the right to refuse an applicant if the home situation is incompatible with the needs of the rescue dog. Rescue is about doing our best for the dog. We do home and reference checks.  All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and are up to date with current vaccinations, before being placed in their forever homes.

FOSTER HOMES NEEDED! We are always looking for good foster homes. Our rescue is foster based and we can always save more dogs if we have foster homes for them to go into. It is not a long term commitment. We have been able to find good forever homes in a short time. We also welcome volunteers who can help transport dogs and help with our outreach and fund raising efforts. Please contact us if you can help.

animal.description:
I'm a Husky!Everest was born around December 31, 2017 and weighs about 45 pounds. Everest's story is an unfortunate one. It starts when he was purchased as a puppy from a breeder. When Everest was 13 weeks old he was taken to the vet for an eye injury. The vet paperwork says 'child and puppy were playing and puppy cut his eye' the vet and owner concluded that Everest was 'unruly due to three boys under the age of 6 years'. Fast forward a few years and Everest is now being kept in the basement because no one in the home has time for him. Everest is constantly escaping (can you blame him?) and getting taken in by the local dog control. The owners realize this is not the best situation for Everest so they decide to try and sell him for $100. One of the owner's friends hears about this and convinces the owner to surrender the dog so he is not put into another bad situation and potentially used for breeding. We are thankful to have Everest with us and he is now neutered and ready to go to his forever home. We will be looking for a very specific home for Everest so he never has to be thrown away again. Husky experience is a must as well as a secure, physical fenced-in yard. We also want Everest to have another playful, sturdy, decent sized dog in his next home to run and play with. Lastly, we will be looking for a home with no kids or older teenage kids only and adults that understand Everest had an unfortunate start to his life and will need some time and understanding. We promised Everest we won't let him down and we know there is a home somewhere that is going to be perfect for him. Traditionally Huskies are not good with cats and Everest follows this tradition. The Adoption Fee for this dog is $300.00.
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

FOSTER HOME URGENTLY NEEDED. Sikorsky is currently located in northcentral Connecticut. If you have room in your heart and home to give a hound a second chance, please fill out an ONLINE FOSTER HOME APPLICATION at our website.

Sikorsky is a gorgeous 5 year old Bluetick boy that needs a foster home while he waits for his forever home. Weighing in at 75 lbs, he loves nothing more than being with his people and getting some loving. His tail never stops wagging and he is a sweet, gentle boy that is joyfully exuberant about food and toys. He got along with both the small and large dog in his foster home and loves everyone he meets. He is cratetrained and housetrained, but has not been left alone loose in the house due to his desire to make his own fun with things he shouldn't. He is not an especially vocal dog, but has a deep, raspy bay. He needs continued work with his basic manners (leash walking/sit/down/stay). Due to his size and some exuberance about food, he is best with older children.

Hi, I'm Princess! I'm a super gentle, sweet girl with a cute smile! I adore my donut bed and I love to curl up and nap the day away. I think I will like walks when all this cold white stuff is gone - when I have to do my business, I am very quick! I get along with my both my feline and canine foster siblings. I would rather not go on long walks in the cold and so far I am not interested in being a running buddy. It's the cozy life for me from now on! Although

I'm very good in my crate,

I would love to sleep in the same room with you!

(Littermate to Spirit)

animal.description:
Mr. Beans!
Mr. Beans loves to have his back scratched and likes to be sung to (even off key)  He likes toys too and is super smart!  Mr. Beans has been taught to sit, shake and laydown - he is eager to please, who knows how many tricks Mr. Beans could learn ?! 
Mr. Beans is an energetic 10 month old pup, he weighs 54 pounds.  He will need an active home and a family willing to spend time working with him to help him become the best doggie he can be.
Mr. Beans was not socialized with other dogs prior to coming to the shelter in search of his forever home.  Therefore, at this time he has not learned how other dogs would like to be treated (Mr. Beans is too enthusiastic).  To help with his socialization and to reinforce good manners, he will need to be enrolled in puppy obedience classes as part of the adoption process.   
Mr. Beans is friendly and loving, but at this time, he will need to be the only dog in his forever home but he can have doggie friends (similar to his size) outside of the home. Mr. Beans will need a cat free home.  Due to Mr. Beans energy level and manners, we commend any children in his forever home are teenagers.
animal.name: Mr. Beans

animal.description:
Hi! I am Winnie. I came from the Memphis Animal Shelter when I was a wee pup. The person who adopted me couldn't handle me when I got bigger (duh! puppies grow!). I am in a foster home right now. That means I live with these nice people until my forever family finds me and takes me home.

Let me tell you some stuff about myself.  First of all I LOVE people! And I love kids 12 and up! They are great to play with!  I love going out and about.  I would be good in an active family where there is always stuff to do. My foster mom says I would be good for someone that is outdoorsy and will keep me busy. 

I am house trained and kennel trained, but I am really good in the house and don't tear things up. My Mom says I have "home training." I like going for walks but if I get really excited I pull on the leash. My foster Mom says I am really smart and if I went to doggy obedience school, she is sure I will graduate and get a diploma. That sounds like so much fun! I could learn some tricks!  I am ok with dogs that are around my size. I do not care for cats.

I am fully vetted, up to date on vaccines, tested for heartworms and internal parasites, on heartworm prevention and spayed and microchipped. All I need is a family that will love me as much as I will love them!

I am in a foster home. I am not at the clinic.

Please call my foster Mom, Debby at 901-396-5926 or email her at revsofmathew@earthlink.net. Mom will be handling my adoption.

animal.description:
Meet this handsome hunk named Cameron!! He is the sweetest most laid back dog. He just wants love and affection and he is the easiest boy!! He loves to lay on the couch and be snuggled on and then go for walks and he is so happy. What a total gem!!

Cameron is in a foster home with 3 other dogs and is doing very well with them. He can get posessive over his food and treats if you let him, but with a quick correction he is quick to learn the rules. He would be happy as on only dog but we think he could do well with a female dog who would put him in his place and not let him become dominant. He would also need a strong pack leader to teach him the ropes and be consistent with his training.

He is super sweet and loves to snuggle. He is crate trained and housebroken except for a little marking, but he wears a male diaper with no issues until we can get him neutered. We think he would do well with children that are a little older, 8 and up, so they will be respectful of him and his neglectful past. We are going to say NO cats for this boy because he loves to chase squirrels and has a prey drive. He love to play but also love to be a couch potato and he loves his walks. He is up for a 1-2 mile hike as well but he does not need this much exercise on a daily basis, he is an old soul in a younger dogs body. He would benefit from an easy walk harness as he pulls a bit on the leash. This boy is super smart and catches on quickly. 

Cameron is all up to date on his vaccines, has had a full bloodwork panel done, and also has an appointment to be neutered on January 15th. This is all included in his adoption fee. He is just waiting for the right family to scoop him up!! Are you his FUR-ever home??

animal.description:
My name is Stitch and I am an 8 year old, 85 lb, German Shepherd. Don't let my age fool you though because I am a happy outgoing boy who loves his toys and hoomans. I am potty trained, and I walk well on a leash. I do well and love to be around other dogs, but am not a fan of the felines so I need a home without kitty companions. I have met kids 12 and older but no little ones yet. I would love to meet any kids! I will be a gentle big boy. I am a really laid back and easy going guy and am very friendly and loveable. I was abandoned and ended up in a high kill shelter but I don't let my past get me down. I always have my goofy smile on my face. I have the beginnings of hip dysplasia but have no issues with stairs or walks or excercise. I was just diagnosed with renal disease also known as kidney failure so we don't know my lifespan ahead but I am currently having no issues with that either. (Dogs with renal disease can live several years so Stitch could still have his full lifespan ahead of him). I am undergoing heartworm treatment and only have a slight case of heartworms so I will have a full recovery there! Despite my health challenges, I would be a great companion to any current resident dogs and to the hoomans of any family. My leash manners and potty training are a great plus. I know I'm not allowed on the furniture and I have perfect house manners. I ride great in the car and love car rides too! If you think we would be a good match please follow the instructions below to meet me! 

Stitch is fostered in Lincoln and cannot be viewed at the shelter in Papillion. The adoption fee is $300 and covers age appropriate vaccines, a microchip, and a spay/neuter. The adoption fee helps cover the cost of these vetting procedures. If you want to meet this pet, or are interested in adopting, please submit an inquiry or email to email@townandcountryhumanesociety.org. They will determine if you and/or your family are a fit and if so, provide instructions for completing the application. 

After you have submitted an application and have been approved, we will setup a meet and greet between you and the pet. Applications are reviewed in order of receipt. 

Please be sure to follow us on Facebook to learn more about Town and Country Humane Society and our mission.
animal.name: Stitch (Fostered in Lincoln)

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Hello foxy, Roxy Rocket. She may have a supervillainess name and a masked face, but make no mistake this gal is a super sweet, super adorable pup.

One of our Batman pups Roxy is a large, mixed breed - we think primarily pointer with possibly some hound and lab. Like most bottle fed pups, Roxy craves attention and is very people friendly and longs for a family that will love and pamper her forever. She is learning to walk on a leash, and working on commands, "sit", "down" and "roll over". Roxy is a smart, obedient, happy girl who needs a home that can keep her physically and mentally stimulated and in a good supply of chew toys!

The 9 "Batman" pups arrived at Dolly Goodpuppy on April 23rd at only 2 weeks old. Their mom was unhealthy, malnourished, and could not feed or care for her pups. They came in heavily loaded in parasites and some had breathing issues. They were bottle fed for over a week, had multiple dewormings, trips to the vet, and various meds. For several it was very touch-and-go for a while. They are all doing great now - strong, feisty, and full of puppy personality - are looking for their forever families.

Approximate DOB -04/09/2019

Adoption fee includes; spay, microchip, vaccinations, and up to date heartworm/flea/tick prevention.

Interested in Roxy? complete our online foster or adoption application at dollygoodpuppy.org

'Zadie is a 2 year old, 45 lb pit mix rescue with a lot of energy and even more love to give! She is sweet, goofy, gets excited easily, likes to play in puddles, and loves to cuddle when she feels safe at home. A strong and energetic girl, Zadie has been through a lot of change, so she can get nervous and reactive in new or high energy situations. She has been in a dedicated board and train facility for the past 2 months to work on her behavior, confidence, and fear reactivity. Zadie needs an experienced dog owner who can provide a calm space, regular exercise, consistent training, and lots of love!A full report on her personality, behavior and needs will be made available to Zadie's adopter. She will do best in a calm and structured home environment. Zadie is smart, loveable, and will make a wonderful companion for someone who has the time, experience, and energy to give her all the love and attention she needs!'

She is house trained, spayed, microchipped, and up-to-date on all vaccinations (records available). Interested adopters can contact me (Carmen Atwater) at 336-346-6035 or carmenatwater@gmail.com. If you need any more information, please do not hesitate to let me know.

These dogs are looking for homes through private parties in the Los Angeles CA area. This page is a service to help individuals in the L.A. area trying to place dogs into loving homes. The dogs listed on this page are not affiliated with Karma Rescue. We have not evaluated the dogs and they are not under our care. We are not responsible for any adoptions through private parties. animal.description:
Hello I’m Haines! I’m a joyful, playful, well behaved dog, about 4 years old and weighing 65 pounds.  My foster mom found me on the side of a country road in Polk county, and when she pulled her truck over and got out, I jumped right onto her seat and stayed there!  I LOVE car rides—Vroom Vroom!  

My foster mom says that I’m a very relaxed, chill guy, even when I’m around other dogs who are acting crazy.  I’m very well mannered.  I love to be covered up with a cozy blanket at night and I love to cuddle as well.  In my mind, I’m a lap dog! My favorite playthings are solo cups, bones, treats, tennis balls and big bouncy balls.  I love kids too!  

I would do best in a house that has a fenced in yard, and where my family isn't gone to work all day long.

If you would like to adopt me (and I sure hope you do!), please reach out to Safe Paws Rescue and they will send you an application to begin the adoption process. Safe Paws is a small rescue, so they accept inquiries from residents in Pinellas County only, please.

Sky is a 4 yr old, female-spayed Pit that is currently with K9 Pawsibilities LLC for training/ foster. She is up for adoption through Paws Fur Life.
She's up to date on vaccines, medium energy with stamina, Enjoys warm summer days, zoomies in the yard, laying in a warm blanket, long walks and spending time with her people. No small animals for this gal as she has strong prey drive. I'd say no other dogs at this point- although her socialization skills with boundaries and impulse control are improving daily.
She must have a fenced in yard, no exceptions.
Kids over the age of 6 in the home are okay. She really likes people, but is a bit of a powerhouse so she will need someone who is comfortable with being strict when it comes to spacial boundaries, consistent rules, structure and getting her daily exercise.
She is crate trained, walks beautifully on leash(with a prong collar and shock collar), rides well in the car and is continuing to improve with her manners around people and animals.
This gal could make a structured person or the right couple a very nice companion. Please share so we can find this beautiful gal a great forever home.
Adoption Fee: $350 to Paws Fur Life

Fill out an application for Sky at:

ttps://www.cognitoforms.com/PawsFurLife1/PuppyDogAdoptionApplication

Sky is not a Rose's Rescue dog. Please fill out the application with Paws For Life Rescue.

This guy burrows into you both physically and emotionally; it is hard not to adore him!

Hux has plenty of puppy energy and playfulness, but also settles and can be a couch potato once his daily exercise needs are met. He is very playful with dogs and his best friend is his former family's other dog, Sissy (already adopted through SOS), but he is also living with four senior dogs right now and is not annoying to them! Hux would make a great addition to a household as the only dog or as a buddy to a playful existing family dog(s). He is interested in going new places and meeting new people, but can be hesitant of strangers at first, men moreso than women, and has shown some reactivity when on leash. His former family had two toddlers who he was very gentle with, but Hux would do best in an adult-only household with limited family members, as the additional activity and foot traffic that children and/or roommates bring would likely not be a great fit for Hux, at least not until he builds his confidence and social skills.

He is house trained and loves going on walks but could use a little work on his leash skills as he tends to pull; he walks much better in an Easy Walk harness. Hux is a pretty quiet boy but he may bark to get your attention or alert you of something he hears/sees. He also shows overexcitement and reactivity on the leash when he sees other dogs and some people. His adopters will need to be committed to working on this in slow, small doses, and he would be best suited for a neighborhood that is not super busy.

A fenced yard would be ideal so he could run and play safely, but if that's not available he'll need lots of leash walks and opportunities for off-leash play in a fenced area. His preferred playstyle is wrestling, boxing and bitey-face, but he is also very socially appropriate with dogs that he has been properly introduced to and reads their body language very well...but he will try all his tricks to try to engage another dog in play.

A basic training course is a must for Hux, to help teach him good manners and commands, further his socialization and confidence with other dogs and people, and help build that very important bond between him and his human(s). Additionally, private training to reduce his leash reactivity will be critical, especially if his adopters plan to leash-walk him in populated areas regularly.

Hux is a gentle, happy, SNUGGLY boy who just wants a loving forever home. Can you make his dream come true? Fill out an application today and let him know that you'd love to have him join your family!

Hux's Story: Hux and his pal Sissy were surrendered by their owners as they felt they could no longer provide the attention they need with two toddlers and another child on the way.

Adoption Fee: $585

To apply for this dog, fill out an adoption application on our website: www.sosarl.org/aa/

**Additional info you should know - For most of our dogs, we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each of our dogs as an individual and do our best to describe and place them based on personality not breed label. Some dogs may not yet be in New England, nor ready for immediate adoption. There may be additional vetting, quarantine, waiting periods and/or fees depending upon your state of residence. If you have questions or concerns on any of this, you can discuss this with your Adoption Counselor.

animal.description:
Charley       8-year-old male black Lab mix      99-lb     Neutered
 
Background:  
Found near the I-5 highway by a San Joaquin County Sheriff in mid-October, this guy was suffering from a badly broken left hind leg.   His femur bone was shattered – likely a result of being hit by a car.  After extensive surgery and the installation of titanium hardware to hold his femur together, a battle with challenging bacterial infection at the site of the injury began.  We pulled him from a central valley shelter hoping to nurse him through his recovery, but Charley’s life became in jeopardy due to the expanding bacterial infection that his body and antibiotics could not resolve.  He was also putting very little weight on the leg even though the surgery was almost two months ago – the bone was not healing properly.  Charley (given that name by the shelter) had his leg amputated a few days before Christmas – talk about a lump of coal – but at least Charley is alive.
 
Nothing slows down Charley -- https://youtu.be/SBXQ9WBncc4
Charley bopping around his foster home -- https://youtu.be/DdY6bgKdt20
 

What Charley’s foster says:    
Charley is 100 lbs of sweetness.  This amazing boy has been through so much and still has so much love to give.  He is super friendly with people and other dogs.  He’s currently living with our 6-year-old female Lab and has been around a couple of other family’s pups and is always friendly.  

Not sure about cats, although I know he’s a squirrel chaser.  He spotted one on the fence in our backyard and took off after it.  Because of his post-surgery recovery  he has been spending most of his time inside.  

He is fully housetrained.  He sleeps mostly on the couch or on a dog bed because it’s unsafe for him to maneuver getting upstairs to our bedrooms, at least for the time being.  Charley has been left alone in the house multiple times with no issues.  The only times I’ve heard him bark are when the doorbell rings and when I’m returning home; he will bark at the door, just excited for me to walk in.  Charley also feeds off the energy of our own dog so he may not even do that if he’s the only pup.  He sometimes startles and gets scared of loud, abrupt noises so he may not be a fan of 4th of July fireworks.   

He loves his food and treats and will sit, stay, and wait for me to say “ok” to eat it.  He definitely knows “sit” and “stay” and comes when you call him.  Charley loves to have his ears scratched.  Sometimes he snores as loud as my husband.  He is a cuddler (or a nuzzler as I call him).  He loves to nuzzle in right next to you for pets and sometimes tries to be a 100-lb lap dog.  He has been recovering amazingly from his surgery and has adjusted so well.  I think if dogs could talk he would be saying that he is so thankful that he was saved and that he is ultimately much happier on 3 legs.  Whoever adopts sweet Charley is hitting the jackpot!
 
What Charley’s Rescue Rep says:   
What a wonderful spirit and attitude for so much that he has gone through.  He was not using that injured leg much at all when he first joined our program and is getting around exceptionally well now that the leg is completely gone.  We except him to recover fully from the amputation surgery and live a long and fulfilling life on just three legs.  He is one big dog – not really that overweight – do not know sure what he is mixed with.  Charley will need some work on walking on a leash as he pulls quite hard on the leash.  Would do fine in a home with or without another dog.  Might be a bit too exuberant for small children or someone unsteady on their feet. 
 
Medical:  With the exception of lacking one of his back legs, Charley is in great shape.  He is current on Rabies and distemper vax, heartworm negative, neutered,  and microchipped.
 
Charley is located in:  Napa.
 
If you are interested in Charley, please contact Rescue Rep Dave at 415-686-4248 or david.c.ely@sbcglobal.net

animal.description:
Meet Charlie! He is a 4 year old pitbull mix. He came to us in November 2020 from a shelter partner in Georgia, when they no longer had space for him. He already knows basic commands such as sit, stay, heel and down. He walks pretty well on a leash, making him the perfect walking or running partner! While this energetic boy loves to be outside, he will curl up with you after a long day for some snuggles! He likes some other dogs, but he can be a bit picky about his friends so if you have another dog at home, they'd have to meet first! He gets a little fussy over the cats at the shelter, so we think he'd do best in a home with no cats. If your looking for the perfect hiking/walking dog, or just a lovable companion, Charlie is your dog! 

Charlie has lived in a home previously and was in our 'Home for the Holidays' foster program! His foster said he was nervous at first, but was very food motivated making it easier for him to settle in! They said he was very obedient and eager to learn! In his previous home, he lived with children and they were a bit too much for him, so he'd do best in a home with adults only. He has interacted with some of our staff's children and done well, but he gets easily overwhelmed by them. 

If interested in adopting Charlie, please submit an online adoption application! Due to COVID-19, all animal meetings must be scheduled by appointment. Once we receive and review your application, we will contact you to schedule an appointment! Thank you!

animal.description:
Meet Bruno.  He was surrendered by his owner who had him since he was 6 weeks old.  Picture when baby included to prove this.  He was born 12/10/2018.  He was told Bruno was a full blooded German Shepherd but we believe him to be a mix.  Maybe with German Shepherd and another Shepherd type or Boxer.  His owner had him as an indoor pet his entire life and really loved him.  However, Bruno has allergies to fleas and had experienced flea dermatitis that was untreated for so long that his skin on his leg and especially his back was in really bad and sore condition when we took him in.  The owner felt bad and said he never treated him with a vet just meds he could buy at the store that never worked.  He said Bruno deserves better.  We took him to the vet and he had a really bad bacterial infection on his back and legs an is being treated for a full month with antibiotics and steriods.  We plan for a full recovery.  His owner had to move out of state for another job due to loss of job from COVID times and was forced to give him up.  It was a sad day for his owner but he knew he would be better off medically.  We had Bruno's shots updated and he is heartworm negative.  He was treated for intestinal worms and is on flea meds now.  We will have him neutered and microchipped once his skin condition is resolved.  Having surgery with bacterial infection on his skin was pretty risky for his recovery per the vet.  We are hoping to have him neutered in February.  He is shy at first but once he knows you is really sweet.  He was with another dog that was small in his first two years of life.  He loves to chase a tennis ball.  Due to his skin issue and not being around young kids, we reccommend kids over 7 as the young ones may scare him.  He has a sweet soul and deserves the best.

Bruno's adoption fee is $350 and will help cover his vet bills.  

If you are interested in Bruno, apply at our main page at www.lifehouse.petfinder.com.  If you have questions about Bruno, contact Holly via text or call at 615-310-5996.

animal.description:
"Hi. Thanks for visiting me online! My name is Brooklyn and I am around 4 years old, new to the adoptable doggy crew and I can’t wait to move into my forever home. I'm all set to join my new family - already spayed, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations.

I'm currently staying with a foster family who is learning more about me.  My foster momma describes me as a shy and nervous girl. I am looking for the right home that is patient and can help me feel more comfortable with my surroundings. 

My foster momma thinks my ideal home would be an adult only home with a secure fenced in yard. I do love to have fun running, building up to full-on zoomies! No apartments or city lifestyles for me. There are too many loud noises that I am unsure of and frighten me. As for animal roommates, I prefer male dogs over females. I can get a bit competitive, so my doggie BFF will be a well balanced, social, easygoing pup! Cat roommates? No thanks - they're just not for me.

I know that I'm super adorable, but I am looking for a home experienced with fearful dogs like me. I'm a sensitive girl who needs an understanding home. If you are serious about embarking on this journey with me, please email your completed adoption profile (found here: https://providenceac.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Adoption-Profile.pdf) to cmuller@providenceac.org with an explanation of your experience with fearful dogs. 

Tail wags and kisses - Brooklyn"

____


Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. To find out this pet’s adoption fee or for more information, please call the Adoption Center with this pet’s ID number.

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

Meadow 
#themylofoundation
Florida / Alabama 

How could someone look into those eyes and literally not come back for her?! Meadow has the saddest eyes but her eyes tell a story of her past. Her past has been full of neglect, heartbreak, people who haven’t kept their word with her. Meadow wishes she had a family who really understood she is such a loving and caring dog. She hopes that someone sees her and just can’t get her out of their mind. Meadow wants someone to take a chance and experience an amazing life with her. She wants to be so loved so bad but she doesn’t think it’s possible anymore. In this big world, Meadow just wants one person to tell her she’s beautiful and actually mean what they say.

ADOPTION PENDING - NOT ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS AT THIS TIME

Doherty is a handsome one year old hound new to our rescue. He came to us from a shelter in Ontario - they found him as a stray.
Doherty is friendly with everyone he meets. Initially he was uneasy being in a house - it seems he was an outdoor dog before his rescue. 
He was nervous of the stairs and hardwood floors but with lots of praise and positive training he is gaining confidence.
Doherty loves his walks but like all hounds - he must be always be on leash and only off-leash in a safely fenced back yard.

Soon Doherty will be neutered. We have done thorough testing, completed his vaccines and he was microchipped.
We know he will do well in his forever home.

animal.description:
Meet Molly! This 11 yr old 30lb Beagle Mix is ready to find her new home! Molly is a sweet gal who is looking for that perfect retirement home. A calm quiet household would be best for an older gal like her. While she has lived with kids in the past, we do think she would do better with no kids, or older kids with prior dog experience. Her gentle personality and love of her people makes her the perfect companion pup. 

Molly loves being with her people so much that a family with someone home often is ideal. She has lived with cats before, so kitty siblings are a possibility, and she has made a doggy friend here at the shelter, so a dog-respectful-dog sibling is a possibility as well (meet and greet with other dogs is a must). 

Molly has a few medical concerns. She appears to be deaf and has cataracts, but still has decent vision. She also has a grade V/VI heart murmur and severe spine, hip, and wrist arthritis. She has responded well to pain and joint medication, and loves to trot around and sniff everything with her beagle nose! 

Despite being a little old lady Molly still has a lot of spunk, and would love a nice retirement home to spend her golden years!

Interested in this beautiful senior? Give us a call to schedule an appointment. Meets by appointment only. 518-885-4113. 

*If you are a Saratoga County resident 60 or older, the adoption fee is waived for Molly.

animal.special_needs_notes:
Molly has a few medical concerns. She appears to be deaf and has cataract, but still has decent vision. She also has a grade V/VI heart murmur. X-rays were done that show some enlargement of the heart, but luckily no fluid in her lungs. Medications should be discussed with your vet.

She also has severe spine, hip, and wrist arthritis, worst in her left hind leg. She has responded well to pain and joint medication, and loves to trot around and sniff everything with her beagle nose! 

She also has a few lumps on her body that appear to be fat, benign skin tags, and benign adenomas. She also has Lyme disease. Bloodwork and a urinalysis we done on Molly and were totally normal. Despite being a little old lady Molly still has a lot of spunk, and would love a nice retirement home to spend her golden years!

We are a foster home based rescue organization. **Only approved adopters can meet our dogs** 

If you are interested in adopting please follow these instructions before contacting Rescue4All. Virtually all of your questions will be answered by following these instructions: 

1. Go to our website www.rescue4all.org 
2. Thoroughly read through the HOW TO ADOPT tab
3. Thoroughly read through the OUR PROCESS tab
4. then fill out an online application from your laptop or desktop computer or click on the mobile friendly link on the application page.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Aurie  is about a year old and is likely a Treeing Walker Coonhound or Harrier Hound or maybe a mix . 

What we know about her is that she is not your typical hound, She is relatively quiet and mellow. 

She likes to play with play with her foster dog sister, but would do best in a cat free home. 

She would like an active home who has researched or knows about the hound breed. 

We are working potty training, crate training, leash skills, and basic commands like sit, stay, come.

She is food motivated and will show you her teeth in a “smile” when you feed her or just get home from being gone for a bit. 

She is a total cuddle bug and loves attention!

animal.description:
Beautiful Kiara is a 2 year old, 40 pound Pit Bull mix, who is just as sweet as can be. She can be a little shy around people she doesn’t know, but no one remains a stranger for long with this sweetheart. Affectionate and loving, she quickly becomes everyone’s favorite companion. Kiara is house trained, has wonderful manners, and rides well in the car. She is not a fan of her crate, but her foster family tells us that she is not destructive and has been trustworthy in the home. Nothing makes Kiara happier than playing in the yard with the kids and foster dog sibling, and she will settle down easily on her bed afterward for a nap. She is truly the best dog! 

Kiara was picked up as a stray by Animal Control in South Carolina. They could see she had recently had puppies, but sadly the puppies were nowhere to be found. This dear, gentle girl has been thriving in her foster home and enjoying all the loving attention family life has to offer. She deserves a wonderful forever family of her own, and would do well in a home with children or a companion dog.  You don't want to miss out on this amazing girl!


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
COLLABORATION WITH READY FOR RESCUE

Devin is a lovable, goofy, playful 2-year-old Pit Mix who was rescued from a high kill shelter in South Carolina. He's a real cuddle bug and he'll happily hang out with his head in your lap while you work at your computer. He's also fond of sleeping next to you. He's got a great disposition and his friendly to everyone he meets. He loves going on walks and he would make a great hiking companion (and he's good in the car).

Devin is a smart cookie who knows his basic commands and really wants to please. He's also quite content to hang out on the couch and nibble at his chew toys. Devin is a super sweet dog and would make a great family dog. He's a big guy (65 lbs) and he is active so he would probably do best in an active home with older kids. We are sure he would love a yard! Inquire about this lovable lug today.
 
Pioneers for Animals Welfare Society, Inc.
http://www.paws-li.org
Phone: (631) 306-4616

animal.description: Hi! My name is Buster and I was rescued from a shelter in Georgia before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I am a super friendly boy who just loves to howl, bark, and talk to everyone. I like to play with all other dogs, regardless of their size, and I would be an excellent fit for a family with children looking for a dog to pal around with. An experienced dog owner would probably be best for me and I know I would be happiest living in a home with a big yard for me to run around in. I could benefit from some further training, particularly potty-training because I haven't quite mastered that yet, but I do let myself in and out of my kennel when I need to use the bathroom here on the ranch. I know how to sit and shake, and I've also started learning how to walk on a leash. I would love it if I could have a new owner who could help me learn lots of new and fun things!

animal.description:
On December 28th, we were contacted by a local shelter about an 8 week old puppy who looked like he had chemical burns to his face. After seeing a vet, he was diagnosed with puppy strangles. We named him Jelly Bean and he stayed in the hospital for 48 hours. He went to his foster home, where he has been for 33 days, and flourished like no other! Not only does his face look 100 times better, he is also feeling great and his little personality is awesome! He is such a smart, big boy! He is currently 13 weeks old and weighs 27lbs. He is going to be a big boy, as we were told he is a Border Collie mixed with a Saint Bernard. We can believe it! He likes to heard by nipping his foster brothers and sister in the side, biting in the butt and you know....several other hearding ways...that’s his job, so he thinks. Ha. 

Jelly Beans foster mom thinks he would be very cat curious and a home with laid back cats or no cats at all would be best. He LOVES other dogs, but a playful companion would be the best fit for him. He is also pretty good at entertaining himself, another dog is not required. Jelly bean has been exclusively working on potty training. He does a great job of not going potty in his crate while his foster mom is at work. He is also crate trained. Jelly Bean would do best with kiddos older than 5, due to his rambunctiousness. 

Jelly Bean is your typical puppy, but just a tad bit more rambunctious. A family with loads of time for him and extra love to give, is his dream family. He also told his foster mom a home with good food and toys is a must. We promised him that! Do you have loads of time and love, good toys and good food for our boy Jelly Bean? If so, hop on over to our website and fill out an application! https://sianimalrescue.org Jelly Beans adoption fee is $200 and includes his neuter, age appropriate vaccines, deworming, microchip with registration and he has been current on heartworm, flea and tick prevention.

Located in Jeffersonville, IN.



Adoption fee $200
** To arrange a meeting go to www.sianimalrescue.org and submit an application**
 I will come (Neutered, current on vaccines, micro chipped, fecal, heart worm tested if age appropriate, monthly flea and tick prevented, dental if recommended by our vet.

If you are already in love with me you have the option of reserving/pre adopting after your application has been approved. Te quickest way to be considered as an adopter for a dog is to immediately submit an adoption application which can be found on our website, www.sianimalrescue.org

If you can't adopt this pet please consider being a sponsor. Just $5 will help towards to care of this baby. We are 501c3 non profit, contributions may be tax exempt.
     
Our organization offers 24PetWatch microchips, which include free registration into the 24PetWatch pet recovery service. For more information visit www.24petwatch.com or call 1-866-597-2424.                                                                                          This pet also is eligible for 30 days of pre-paid ShelterCare pet health insurance. For more information please visit www.sheltercare.com or call 1-866-375-PETS.

Our dogs are split between residence at our shelter, Camp Pawsawhile Retreat, and foster homes. Meet and greets are available by appointment only. Please complete an adopter profile to set up your meet and greet: http://coastalpetrescue.org/adopt/profile

Adoption Fees:
Kittens: $60, Cats (1 year plus): $50, Puppies: $250, Adult Canines (1 to 6 years): $200, Seniors (7 years plus): $100 (unless otherwise specified). Adoption fees are not a tax-deductible donation as allowed by IRS regulations. Adoption fees help to offset the cost of the pet's care incurred by Coastal Pet Rescue, which are generally 2 to 3 times the adoption fee amount.
Some special circumstances may change the fee; see pet's listing for actual adoption fee.

All Coastal Pet Rescue pets are current on shots, microchipped* and spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Adopters are responsible for any shots that may be due after adoption (particularly for kittens and puppies that must have three rounds of shots to be protected).

Microchip:
CPR has implanted a microchip as part of the adoption process and the chip is included in the adoption fee. However, some chip companies require a registration fee varying from $9.99 to $19.99. The registration fees are the responsibility of the adopter and are NOT included in the CPR adoption fee. Adopters may add this cost to their adoption fee to have CPR register the chip on their behalf.

30 Days Pet Insurance: 
As a Petfinder member, all adopters are entitled to a free 30 day insurance policy through PetFirst. Coastal Pet Rescue is not responsible for this policy. Adopters must call PetFirst’s toll-free number 855-710-7387 to activate the coverage. If adopters fail to call, the policy will not be activated.

Olaf is about one year old and is a smaller Pitty boy, around 35 lbs. He is super sweet, has a very high toy drive, great with other dogs.
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00 . This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

Tate is an amazing 18 month-2 year old Aussie mix. He was born blind and hearing impaired, but that does not slow him down one bit. He navigates around very well and learns new places very quickly. This active guy weighs about 35-40lbs. He loves playing in the backyard with his foster siblings and snuggling with his humans. Every time you look at him it’s hard not to smile because he is just such a happy fella. He is sure to bring lots of happiness and love in his forever home. He loves people and is the definition of “velcro dog.” Tate is housetrained when kept on a schedule. He rides well in the car and walks well on a leash. Exploring the yard and going on walks are two of Tate’s favorite things to do.

Tate is up to date on vaccines and preventatives, neutered, and microchipped. He is currently being fostered in Huntsville, AL. If you are interested in making Tate a forever part of your family please fill out a non-binding application for him at www.forrescue.net/dog-application.

This dog is with Survivor Tails Animal Rescue (STAR) please fill out an application: survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions. Be sure to tell them ARK sent you!  

Meet Percy, a 6-year old male Great Pyrenees / Lab mix located in the Boston area. At one hundred pounds, he’s a lot of dog to wrap your arms around and his heart is as big as his body. He is neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, and available for foster or adoption in Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Connecticut through our furr-iends at Survivor Tails Rescue. 

Percy is a beach bum and nature lover. He enjoys hanging out with people at home or on the trails. He loves to hike and swim, and would thrive with an active, nature-loving owner. He is loyal towards friends and family but wary of strangers, especially men. He prefers the ladeez, so his family will include an experienced female family member.

Percy has certain home and family needs to ensure his success, including a quiet child-free environment with little comings and goings. He also needs to be the only fur-kid. A big boy like Percy needs space to roam and stretch his legs, so he’s specifically looking for a single-family home with fenced-in yard. 

Luckily, Percy loves to learn and will be attending a board and train program prior to joining his new family in hopes of boosting his confidence and social prowess. With such valuable training on his resume, his family must be willing and able to keep up his skills. 

Percy will need an active, experienced family, but his loyalty makes him well worth the effort. If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please fill out an application at survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions. PLEASE tell them ARK sent you! #ARKforPercy

animal.description:
Pistol Pete is a 2 year old male Chihuahua mix who came from Texas. He has a great personality and is very feisty. 
Pistol Pete came to Prairie Paws with a group of dogs in a kill shelter in Texas. Pete is getting used to other pets in the foster home including dogs his size, cats and young respectful kids.
Pistol Pete was not neutered when he came to our rescue,  so he has been marking(peeing) on things. You see him in a belly band in several pictures.  He was neutered on 12/29-so the marking usually subsides after a few weeks. The adopter will need to follow routines the foster family uses for house and crate training. While being neutered,  the vet found a b.b. inside him-so apparently he was shot at before coming to us. The b.b. was removed 
This lovable  little guy uis not sure what to think about the cold ND winters as he probably has never seen snow and cold in Texas.
Pistol Pete will make some one a great little companion.
All medical work is completed prior to adoption including neutering shots worming flea treatment rabies shot micro chip heartworm test and vet exam. 
The adoption fee is $150 +tax with an approved application.  The application is on the website www.prairiepawsrescue.com and go to the adopt link to download the jotform application fill it out and submit. 
Prairie Paws Rescue does not adopt on a first come basis but who will provide the best home suited to the pets needs.
animal.name: Pistol Pete

animal.description:
Meet Jazzy! Jazzy is a coonhound that lets her love shine! She is estimate to be around 12 months old and currently weighs ~ 43 pounds. She was very thin when she came to us and is steadily putting on weight. her idea weight is ~ 50 pounds. She is very friendly, great with other dogs, and has beautiful markings with big brown soulful eyes. Jazzy is full of personality. She is eager to learn and interested in anything you are doing at anytime. She loves to be walked outside and her nose is to the ground following her scents like a true hound.  She does howl like a  typical coonhound and is quite vocal. Ideally, we are looking for an individual, couple, or family that is familiar with this breed. She would do well with an active individual or couple that enjoys active walks or hiking trails as she loves to explore outdoors. She would do well in a basic training class as she is super food motivated and eager to please. She will follow you around the house and has some mild separation when left alone. She does love to cuddle up with her person and relax while you watch a good movie, take naps, or just enjoy a lazy day  together.  If  you are looking for a fun loving gal that is happy-go-lucky and so sweet, Jazzy is your girl!!
Jazzy's adoption fee will be $300 and includes Rabies, Distemper/parvo, and Bordetella vaccines, heartworm tested( negative). , dewormed, current on prevention and microchipped 

If you would like to be considered in adopting our pet(s), you must FIRST complete an adoption application. To submit an adoption application click on "More About Us", located on the right (bottom) of the page. This will route you to our home page where you select the "Adoption Application" tab located on right side of the page. The application will open in a "WORD" document format where you select "enable editing" on the top of the application, then complete the form and email to rhonda4care@gmail.com. Please make sure you answer all questions on the application. If you don't have WORD format, email rhondad4care@gmail.com and use "adoption application" in the subject line.

We are not a shelter. All of our animals live in private homes in foster care. Upon approval of your application, you will be contacted by the pet's foster parent to ask questions and to set up a time to meet the pet of interest.

Our dogs are split between residence at our shelter, Camp Pawsawhile Retreat, and foster homes. Meet and greets are available by appointment only. Please complete an adopter profile to set up your meet and greet: http://coastalpetrescue.org/adopt/profile

Adoption Fees:
Kittens: $60, Cats (1 year plus): $50, Puppies: $250, Adult Canines (1 to 6 years): $200, Seniors (7 years plus): $100 (unless otherwise specified). Adoption fees are not a tax-deductible donation as allowed by IRS regulations. Adoption fees help to offset the cost of the pet's care incurred by Coastal Pet Rescue, which are generally 2 to 3 times the adoption fee amount.
Some special circumstances may change the fee; see pet's listing for actual adoption fee.

All Coastal Pet Rescue pets are current on shots, microchipped* and spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Adopters are responsible for any shots that may be due after adoption (particularly for kittens and puppies that must have three rounds of shots to be protected).

Microchip:
CPR has implanted a microchip as part of the adoption process and the chip is included in the adoption fee. However, some chip companies require a registration fee varying from $9.99 to $19.99. The registration fees are the responsibility of the adopter and are NOT included in the CPR adoption fee. Adopters may add this cost to their adoption fee to have CPR register the chip on their behalf.

30 Days Pet Insurance: 
As a Petfinder member, all adopters are entitled to a free 30 day insurance policy through PetFirst. Coastal Pet Rescue is not responsible for this policy. Adopters must call PetFirst’s toll-free number 855-710-7387 to activate the coverage. If adopters fail to call, the policy will not be activated.

animal.description:
Age:10 Weight: 40 Location: Frederick MD Nicknames: Dutchy, Moaning Myrtle, Trixie Good with other dogs?: Yes. But she doesn't like sharing things. She will warn but not start a fight. Dutchy is ok with other dogs, except she has some resource guarding issues. She guards her food, toys and treats. It is mild. Good with cats? unknown, will not be adopted to a home with a cat Good with children? unknown, will not be adopted to a home with kids under 10 Activity Preference: Low maintenance overall but needs quality outside time., Will go with the flow IQ: Average Dutchess's favorite things: Dutchy's two favorite things are soft things and treats. She will only lay on a blanket and hunts something soft to sit or lay on. She also is treat motivated and her butt drops through the floor if there is a treat in your hand. Dutchess is good at: meeting people, meeting dogs, staying in a crate, behaving in the house, going for car rides, walking on a leash Ideal home: no children, someone at home most of the day, a fenced yard Training Needs: needs obedience training Health issues: Dutchy has a peculiar walk. According to the vet, she has some kind of a deformity that does not cause her pain. She also had 5 teeth removed. None of these seem to be causing her issues now.
Things Dutchy is not, or does not enjoy
Dutchy is NOT dog aggressive
Dutchy is not aggressive towards humans
Dutchy is not overly loving
Dutchy does not enjoy being told what to do
Dutchy does not share ANYTHING well
Dutchy is NOT a good runner
Dutchy Is not a model
Things Dutchy is and or likes
Dutchy wants to listen and make you happy, when it is convenient for her
Dutchy loves soft things
Dutchy is vocal about her disapproval of something with wailing and moaning
Dutchy is opinionated and always believes her stance is correct, no matter what
Dutchy does very well in a crate
Dutchy does well with other dogs as long as anything she could "posses" is not available. (Think, water, ice cube, food, toy)
Dutchy is very odd and has very cute mannerisms
Dutchy does very well with routines
Dutchy does great playing a cat, think (pet me, pet me, pet me, then why are you touching me as you get a growl( NOT AGGRESSIVE!))
Dutchy loves a walk around the block twice a day
Dutchy is great at not having accidents in the house
Dutchy is great for watching TV with.
Dutchy will let you know she doesn't want to do something, sometimes with a small growl
Dutchy is good at not chewing things
Dutchy is very good at taking treats
Meet Dutchess
Dutchy is one of a kind! She is a very unique gal who is looking for someone to treat her like the Dutchess of Grantham.
Dutchy has had a tough life and it shows at first. We got her and had her spayed and 5 rotten teeth removed. This damaged the trust we had and she took a long time to warm back up to us. I will break down what we know about Dutchy
Dutchy and routines- Dutchy loves a routine. It only takes her a couple of times and she understands what she is supposed to do, and does it like a champ. We would strongly recommend a routine of breakfast, bathroom breaks, feedings, walks etc. This seemed to help her feel at home. I would highly recommend a regimented routine to help her feel at home during her first couple of weeks. Once she has learned the routine it continues until you break her of it. If you always potty after food, she will expect it every time. Routines are key for her to start.
Dutchy and her Mannerisms Dutchy has some uncanny and odd mannerisms. She has cat-like mannerisms. If she needs attention, she will let you know she needs attention. She has gotten the nickname Moaning Myrtle in our house due to her letting us know she needs something. Her looks and mood are just as funny as she is. She is a dog of many funny looks and moods, you just have to figure out how to read them to know what she needs at that time. If you are willing to put in the work to figure her out, you will be rewarded (with a mouth around your forearm lol).
Dutchy and her resource guarding. Dutchy does have some issues with resource guarding. It isn't all the time and you don't know when she will exhibit these behaviors. One day I can feed her and be in the kitchen with her and all is good. The next day I am not allowed in the kitchen without some growling. She definitely guards toys and chewy treats, which is why we listed her as an only dog. We would be unsure if she guards beds, spots on the floor, etc.
Dutchy and her interaction with other dogs. Dutchy has met and socialized with our dog and it has gone ok so far. As mentioned early, dutchy has some very peculiar mannerisms that include staring and putting her tail straight up. We took this as a sign of aggression at first, but we are thinking now, it is just Dutchy being Dutchy. That being said, she is never left with our dog unsupervised, even for a minute.
Dutchy and her interactions with us. Dutchy is not overly loving, nor overly interactive with us. She prefers a nice soft environment where she feels safe. As mentioned earlier we had her 3 days before her spay and tooth extraction, so we broke any trust we had. She is slowly starting to warm up to us, but still prefers to go her own way. She does want to be near you at times, and will cuddle up if allowed. She also will try to put her whole mouth around a part of your body. We don't allow this behavior, but it does not seem like she is trying to bite or do anything sinister. We refer back to the cat-like behavior of just doing something to do something. Overall she is a funny dog to just sit and watch as she beebops and stumbles across the room.
What Dutchy needs to live her best life. Dutchy needs a home where she is the only dog, free of kids and has a regimented schedule. She needs someone who is patient and understanding and will provide love when Dutchy requires it. She loves a walk or two a day and enjoys smelling all the things. She is a special little girl who, while odd, is a great companion and will make someone happy.
Don't let the above scare you. The best way to describe dutchess is to give you an analogy. I'm sure we all know the elderly lady at target who runs over your foot with her electric wheelchair and then makes you apologize because your foot was in her way. Next thing you know, you are sitting having a glass of whiskey with said lady and enjoying your time....that elderly lady is dutchess.

Keegan is a 16 month old American Pit Bull Terrier located in Evergreen. She weighs 52 pounds and is a beautiful tan brindle with golden eyes. She is spayed and up to date on all vaccinations and is in very good health. She is full bred and came from a reputable breeder in California. She was hand picked from a large litter for her balanced temperament. Both parents also had great temperaments. She has been raised in a loving home in Colorado since she was 8 weeks old. She has a very friendly disposition and is extremely intelligent. She completed a 4 week puppy obedience course with Friends for Life and also an 8 week adult obedience course with Terroux Dog Training by the time she was 8 months old. A lot of time was spent socializing her with people and other dogs through dog socials and daycare, as well as regular trips to places like parks, walks around the lake and trips to Home Depot. She has really good basic obedience and knows commands like sit, down, stand, wait, stay, come. Her obedience is good in the house and on leash outside of the house. As she's only 16 months old, it's still a work in progress off leash outside of the yard. She rides well in a car also.

She is very friendly with other dogs and has spent time off and on leash with a bunch of dogs either playing and walking in the neighborhood or at socials/training. She loves dogs and does really well with all that are not overly dominant or aggressive. She is respectful of older dogs that want space and of not being too rough with smaller ones. Given the opportunity, she really loves to run around with other dogs off leash and play. As far as living with another dog, I think she may really enjoy that, assuming the other dog was a good match. She has a lot of energy but is very good about being calm and relaxed in the house as long as she gets proper exercise and mental stimulation. She has not spent much time around cats but has been very respectful of the cats she met at the vet clinic. Kids over 10 would probably be best. Once again, she is extremely intelligent and loves to learn new things. Tricks, obedience, tasks, it doesn't matter, she loves to learn and is extremely trainable. Want to teach a dog 100 tricks, this is your girl. She is very good about being left in the house out of a crate on her own and is not destructive of anything in the house. She is fully crate trained though the only time she spends in her crate is when she goes in there on her own for a break. She is a pit bull and has to have pit bull appropriate chew toys as she is capable of destroying anything less and may consume parts if she destroys it. I have found the toys that work best for her and can provide those to the new owner and give advice. She does not chew things other than toys she is given. She loves durable chew toys and balls such as the orange Chuck it balls and loves to play fetch. She still loves to be outside during the winter but may require a coat/sweatshirt in the colder months as she has a very short coat.

She's a really good dog and doesn't have any "issues". The only reason she is being rehomed is because I have encountered some unfortunate life circumstances/changes and don't have the time to give her the exercise and attention that she truly deserves. She is a great dog and I just want her to live a happy enriched life with people that love her. Her ideal home would have a large fenced yard where she can really run and play. She is 100% an inside dog when she is not outside playing/walking. Her ideal people would be active as she has a lot of energy and loves to walk, hike, run, explore. She really would enjoy calm, happy people the most. She would love owners that stimulate her through training or activities. It is very important that she does not live with anyone that has anger or anxiety issues as she is a sweet, sensitive girl that responds best to positive reinforcement and a loving, stable environment. She will be an absolute treat to own for the person or family that wants an intelligent, fun girl to enjoy life with. She comes with all the dog supplies you need as far as a crate, beds, leashes, food, toys etc. Any further questions, please call Doug at 303-670-7792 or email at dworld2.0@gmail.com.
