She has really good basic obedience and knows commands like sit, down, stand, wait, stay, come. Her obedience is good in the house and on leash outside of the house. As she's only 16 months old, it's still a work in progress off leash outside of the yard. She rides well in a car also.

She is very friendly with other dogs and has spent time off and on leash with a bunch of dogs either playing and walking in the neighborhood or at socials/training. She loves dogs and does really well with all that are not overly dominant or aggressive. She is respectful of older dogs that want space and of not being too rough with smaller ones. Given the opportunity, she really loves to run around with other dogs off leash and play. As far as living with another dog, I think she may really enjoy that, assuming the other dog was a good match. She has a lot of energy but is very good about being calm and relaxed in the house as long as she gets proper exercise and mental stimulation. She has not spent much time around cats but has been very respectful of the cats she met at the vet clinic. Kids over 10 would probably be best. Once again, she is extremely intelligent and loves to learn new things. Tricks, obedience, tasks, it doesn't matter, she loves to learn and is extremely trainable. Want to teach a dog 100 tricks, this is your girl. She is very good about being left in the house out of a crate on her own and is not destructive of anything in the house. She is fully crate trained though the only time she spends in her crate is when she goes in there on her own for a break. She is a pit bull and has to have pit bull appropriate chew toys as she is capable of destroying anything less and may consume parts if she destroys it. I have found the toys that work best for her and can provide those to the new owner and give advice. She does not chew things other than toys she is given. She loves durable chew toys and balls such as the orange Chuck it balls and loves to play fetch. She still loves to be outside during the winter but may require a coat/sweatshirt in the colder months as she has a very short coat.

She's a really good dog and doesn't have any "issues". The only reason she is being rehomed is because I have encountered some unfortunate life circumstances/changes and don't have the time to give her the exercise and attention that she truly deserves. She is a great dog and I just want her to live a happy enriched life with people that love her. Her ideal home would have a large fenced yard where she can really run and play. She is 100% an inside dog when she is not outside playing/walking. Her ideal people would be active as she has a lot of energy and loves to walk, hike, run, explore. She really would enjoy calm, happy people the most. She would love owners that stimulate her through training or activities. It is very important that she does not live with anyone that has anger or anxiety issues as she is a sweet, sensitive girl that responds best to positive reinforcement and a loving, stable environment. She will be an absolute treat to own for the person or family that wants an intelligent, fun girl to enjoy life with. She comes with all the dog supplies you need as far as a crate, beds, leashes, food, toys etc. Any further questions, please call Doug at 303-670-7792 or email at dworld2.0@gmail.com.

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs are also microchipped.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description:
"Well, hello there! Thanks for visiting me online! My name is Crawford, and I am around 4 years old and about 54 pounds. I just joined the adoptable doggy crew at Providence Animal Center after traveling here from Georgia, and I can’t wait to move into my new forever home. My adoption day is all I can think about, so please don’t make me wait too long!

The staff & volunteers are still getting to know me, but so far they've learned that I'm a playful, cautious, curious pup who has been known to catch a case of the zoomies now and again!

They think that I'd likely do well living with kid pals who are age 8 & older, if the home's general noise & commotion level doesn't rival that of a circus! As I'm still getting used to all the stressful changes in my world after living with the same family for my entire life down south, I will thrive with a forever family who has the time and patience to help me blossom into the best me that I can be. 

I've really been enjoying spending time with the volunteers here who give me time out of my kennel. I'm even starting to lean in for pets and giving smooches :)

I'm all set to join my new family - already neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations.  So, if you'd like to meet me in person, just schedule an appointment here: ProvidenceAC.org/AdoptADog. I have my bags all packed - I just need my forever family to find me. XOXO ~Crawford

P.S. Someone is so excited for me to find my fur-ever home, that they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! Woohoo!!"

-------
During your appointment, you will be able to meet a selection of pets in the Kennels or Cattery that day. New pets are arriving daily!
-------

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. To find out this pet’s adoption fee or for more information, please call the Adoption Center with this pet’s ID number.

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description:
Colby
Chihuahua/Dachshund Mix
Gender: Male
DOB: 12/14/2011
Adoption Fee: $150.00
Colby a handsome older man looking to see out his senior years with his very own human companion. Colby's not a demanding dog, he just wants the security of a loving home with someone that can take him on leisurely walks and will let him curl up next to them while watching a movie. Adopting a senior dog has so many rewards, please consider making Colby your new best friend!!!Please read the animal bios completely before requesting additional information as we do our best to answer the most frequently ask questions in these bios. 

In order to adopt one of our animals an application must be submitted and approved. You can find these applications by going to http://humanemorgan.org/index.php?page=adoption 

ABOUT ADOPTING FROM THE HSMC: 
The shelter address is 1170 Fairground Rd. Madison, GA 30650. For more information on any of our pets, please feel free to email us at INFO@HUMANEMORGAN.ORG give us a call at 706-343-9977. 
All dogs are heartworm negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
All cats are FeLv/FIV negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
We are open 10am-5pm Monday-Saturday, we schedule our last adoption at 4pm everyday to allow our staff enough time to feed and walk dogs. 
We are an animal shelter and therefore are not able to individually potty train our residents. Many adult dogs do arrive ""house broken"" however due to animal behavior any change in environment will make an emotional impact on the animals and therefore initiate unwanted behaviors during the acclamation period. Please keep this in mind. Puppies do not have the biological maturity to maintain absolute bladder or bowel control and will require a certain degree of potty training and house breaking. Please consider the time and commitment it takes to provide the necessary building blocks for these special babies, prior to submitting your application. 
If you have any questions please email us at info@humanemorgan.org and provide name of the animal you are interested in, in the subject line. 
Thank you, HSMC Staff 

ADOPTION FEES Adoption Fees may change without notice. Always verify the fee when finalizing the adoption. 
~ Cats and Kittens ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $100 
* 1-5 Years = $75 
* Over 5 Years = $50 
** Purebred cats and kittens may be subject to special pricing 

~ Mix Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $200 
* 1 -3 Years = $175 
* 4-8 Years = $150 
* Over 8 Years = $100

~ Purebred and Designer Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $375 
* 1-3 Years = $350 
* 4-8 Years = $275 
* Over 8 Years = $150 

~ Medical and Special Needs ~ 
We have rescued dogs and cats which require additional medical care or that have special needs which are not life threatening. In these cases we may require a higher fee to help recoup the costs of their care while at our rescue.

animal.description:
Brandy is one of Peanut's pups! Peanut was in a loving home before coming to the Haven. She had a litter of pups in her home (Jacky, Brandy, and Tootsie!), where they decided to keep all the dogs. The father to these pups was a golden retriever mix, so the puppies have grown to be rather large dogs! The owners, although they had the best intentions, became overwhelmed with the amount of large dogs in their home. 
Brandy is a very pretty brindle colored golden retiever/rhodesian ridgeback mix. She is shy with strangers, but once she gets comfortable, she is very loving! She is used to being an indoor/outdoor dog, and requires a privacy fence (those long legs let her hop over chainlink fences like they are nothing). Brandy has lived with her siblings all her life and done great with them. She is not very outgoing - she seems to follow the lead of other dogs. She is a very submissive giant who would do great as a playmate for your dog! Brandy is spayed, up to date on shots, microchipped, and has been de-wormed.
DOB: 10/24/2019...All pets have lifetime sanctuary at Haven of the Ozarks. If they cannot remain with their adopter, they must be returned to the Haven.

Adoption fees are as follows: 
Puppies under the age of 6 months - $125
Dogs weighing 30 pounds and less - $125 
Dogs ages 6 months to 5 yrs old - $90
Dogs over the age of 5 yrs old - $75.
Cats under the age of 6 months old - $75
Cats over the age of 6 months old - $65

animal.description:
PLEASE READ BEFORE INQUIRING:
Deputy and Tobias were incredibly neglected in their previous home. They were used to breed and that's it - they were never pet, never inside a home, and never knew real love. Due to the environment they grew up in, they are absolutely terrified of people - they will run away from every person they see, and will bite if cornered. Deputy and Tobias are dogs that will need an experienced dog owner with absolute dedication and focus. It will be hard work teaching them how to be normal dogs. The one thing they have going for them is that they are comfortable around other dogs. Maybe being in a home with a goofy, happy dog will help them learn a thing or two?
Deputy and Tobias do not have to be adopted together. They had never met each other prior to coming to our facility, although they lived in the same ""home"".

animal.description:
Bonded pair Nova & Blaze are in search of their forever home. Both of these cuties are approx. 7 years old.  Nova is a Dachshund mix weighing 18 pounds. She is the fetch-it queen and will chase and return the ball 50 times if you let her. She is a lil chunky but has lost some weight since she has been with us. Nova loves to be cuddled and rubbed on. 

Blaze is a white long-haired fella. He has a couple of medical issues that are managed easily. Needs Enzyme powder and Cosequin (joint supplement) in the a.m. with food. He is a sweet quiet boy that you don't even notice is there. He lays quietly anywhere. He prefers the backyard doggy deck with a soft bed to lay in the sun until he can't take it anymore and comes trotting in for water ?

These two deserve a home that will shower them with love and affection.

Nova and Blaze are NOT California Pit bull Rescue dogs. They are a courtesy posting for 510 Paws Rescue. Please contact them to receive an application: https://www.facebook.com/510pawsrescue

animal.description:
NOTE: We update our posts daily. If you are reading this, we are still accepting applications. We will NOT respond to "is he available" inquiries. 

Oreo is a one-year-old Terrier Mix. He’s sweet, social, and loves other dogs. Naturally, he’s curious about everything since indoor life is very new to him. Oreo is very playful and has lots of energy. Before joining our squad, he lived outdoors in a crate covered in plastic. He would roam the streets by day and eventually find his way back home. His owner surrendered him to our care; they no longer had an interest in having him. 

He’s acclimated to his foster home and follows his fellow foster sibling’s regimen. He loves to eat and isn’t a picky eater. He loves playtime and zooming around is his favorite thing to do in the backyard. 

Oreo will need more training and a family that will continue to help him transition into a domesticated life. He does show separation anxiety when left alone or barricaded behind a gate. 

If you are interested in adopting Oreo please complete an Adoption Interest Application found on our website under “forms.” 

*PLEASE READ: Traditionally, we personally respond to each submission received. However, due to the current high volume of applications/adoptions, you will receive an acknowledgment/receipt email of your submission.

Because we know each of our heroes personally and know the best setting for them to thrive in, we will ONLY contact applications that best match their requisite needs.

We thank you in advance for your interest to adopt one of our heroes and for your patience through the process.

Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.description:
With all that has been going on we totally forgot to post our newest Pups In Peril family member PEGGY. All this girl wanted for Christmas was to live so we decided to pull her from Beaumont Animal Control where her time had run out and she was scheduled for Euthanasia due to the shelter filling up at a alarming rate and being at capacity. This is a bad time of the year for any dog to be in a shelter. This was her second time there and all we can do now is make sure it was the last time.  Peggy is currently in boarding. The boarding facility tells us that she can be protective of her food. She would probably do best as an only dog. She is very sweet and loving with her care takers. She does not mess in her kennel, so we would venture to say that she is housebroken. 
If you would like to meet this precious girl, please submit an application to www.pupsinperil.org/adoption

animal.description:
Happy Angus is a very affectionate, loyal, high energy Lab/Pit mix boy, who likes to be near his humans all the time. This constantly happy and smiling boy is goofy, funny and constantly entertaining his foster mom. He needs a fenced yard, lots of time to exercise and a strong alpha owner who is the leader of their dog pack if there is more than one dog in the home. He showed up as a stray and the foster mom took him in with a promise to help find him the best home ever. She is working with Critter Cavalry Rescue to do just that.
A new home where he can lounge on the sofa, in a dog bed, be a part of the family happenings with the people surrounding him, would be heaven on earth for him. Right now he has to stay in a small room away from the jealous foster home's dog. The foster mom is making it work by Shuffling things around. We think that Angus is smart and could even be good at agility training and just plain learning show dog skills and tricks and tasks. He is like a sponge who is eager to learn and to please you. If you are looking for dog to devote himself to your every step in life and To love you to the moon and back, then please consider Happy Angus. This Tasmanian high energy devil on the outside is nothing but a marshmallow on the inside. A total package of everything in a dog. Please email us if you are interested at : ccrtennessee@gmail.com

ADOPTION FEE REQUIRED. Contact ccrtennessee@gmail.com.

animal.description:
If you're looking for a Superhero of dogs then Hulk is the boy for you! He is a big boy, about 80-90lbs of pure hunk! He’s always got so many compliments on his walks of how gorgeous he is and how well behaved he is. His coat is like a lightly toasted marshmallow, has dreamy brown eyes and a sweet temperament. Hulk is very sweet and affectionate, who is great with other dogs, but not small dogs and cats please. We think he'd be a wonderful family dog or someone's best friend. He's a long lean doggy machine that's 5 years old and has plenty of energy for that active lifestyle you have or would love to have. Hulk was surrendered to the shelter with his sibling for whatever sad excuse owners gave and his sibling got adopted and poor Hulk got passed up and was rescued minutes to be euthanized. He had a home and now he's ready for a real home, a loving home and this time his forever!! 
     He is neutered,  vaccinated,  chipped, and just waiting to hear from his sweet home!

animal.description:
Hi- I’m Zuma. I am a 2-year-old pointer/husky mix, about 45 lbs. I was adopted from PPITS as a puppy, but my owner couldn’t keep me so I ended up in a shelter! Thankfully, PPITS was able to get me back!

I am very sweet with people. I am getting the hang of my commands and working on leash manners. I am also working on my dog reactivity and getting lots of structure and discipline. I am potty trained and crate trained. 

I love hiking and being active. I would do best with an active person or a couple. If there are children in the home, it would be that they are older (12+). I am still anxious about what happened to me, so I probably would not do well with small children. 

Oh, and I love to cuddle and can’t wait to snuggle up with my forever family!

MONTHLY HEARTWORM DATE:  13th of each month
FOSTER HOME:  Chris, cbly58@icloud.com
RESCUE #:  2020-11-12-01

BIO UPDATE (1/16/21):
Max has settled into our foster home.  He is a very sweet boy. He has embraced daily walks and gets excited when he sees his leash.  He loves to cuddle and being petted and will nudge your hand for more.

Max will let you know when its meal time as that is his favorite time of the day.

He does have some medical issues that require daily medications. That will be an additional cost but he is so worth it.

He sleeps well thru the nite (currently in an open crate). Max gets along well with our female and respects her.  He seems to be fully housetrained (not one accident so far)

Max so deserves his own forever home who will love & care for him-are you that home?

BIO:  Max came from a Shelter in north Georgia. We can’t imagine why anyone would turn him in! In just a few words he’s sweet, friendly, and gets along with all dogs. He does like to beg from the table but we don’t give him people food and no one should.  It's not good for him. Our wish list for Max includes:
  - A fenced yard is a must
  - Another dog or two to pal around with
  - Someone that is home a lot to keep him company because he does love his people
  - No apartments or high-rises

After coming into rescue, Max had his gall bladder removed. He has fully recovered and is doing fine without it!  During his initial vet exam, we also found he has a 4/6 heart murmur but no clinical signs of distress.  He is on two meds to help with the blood flow.

Max loves to cuddle with either you or your dog.  He is one of the easiest fosters we've had.

Please keep in mind that not only will you have the monthly heartworm prevention but you'll also have Vetmedin and Enalapril to purchase each month.  Sadly, Max also has dry eyes so he'll need artificial tears.

Don’t let any of that scare you off... he is a dream to foster! 

============== Information for All Dogs/Adopters ==============

If you have questions about this dog, please feel free to contact the foster home at the email address listed above.  They have the most up-to-date information concerning the dog and would be happy to answer any questions about the animal. 

We welcome out of state and Canadian adoptions, but we will not ship any dog via cargo.  You will have to make arrangements to pick up the dog or for them to go by ground transport.  If you choose transporting by either volunteers through our organization or by paid transporter, there will be an additional $45 fee added for the required Health Certificate. 

We will not adopt into CT, RI, NH, ME, or MA due to strict laws regarding importation of dogs into those states.  If you have an issue with this, you need to take this up with your legislatures.

To understand the adoption process through AADR, please review the Adoption Information on our home page.  Transportation options are outlined on that page in Step 3.

If you are interested in adopting this Dachshund please review Read Before You Adopt and then you can complete an Application.

THANK YOU FOR YOUR INTEREST IN A RESCUE.

Please don't let the distance stand in your way of finding your newest best friend. We have volunteers that will help your "new friend" get up and down the East Coast and MidWest. We just can't get them from one Coast to the other but some day we hope to have enough volunteers to do that as well.  For now, please look for dogs on your coast.

animal.description:
Cuddles is a sweet & gentle Bulldog/Staffy mix who is 4-5 years old and weighs 45 lbs.  She is a playful, friendly, pint-sized pup who truly lives up to her name!  Her greatest joy in life is cuddling with her human & canine companions.  If you're looking for a couch potato who will lay quietly by your side & keep you warm for hours, Cuddles is your girl!  Her history is unknown, but it is clear that she spent much of her life being bred.  She is still learning about life, but has silly puppy antics and an adorable pittie prance.  Cuddles asks that you forgive her sometimes pouty scowl & her mostly serious expression. She wants you to know that her wrinkles and markings do not accurately convey the silly, fun-loving girl she really is.  She is looking for a home with at least one friendly dog she can snuggle with who will help build her confidence as she learns what it’s like to be a loved family member.  She currently lives with three canine friends (two males & one female), but her behavior around cats is unknown.  She is housebroken, crate trained, spayed, fully vaccinated & microchipped. She was HW+ when she came to BarkVille and her treatment will be completed soon.  If you are not familiar with Heartworms, dogs get them from mosquitos and it is not contagious. It is easily prevented & highly treatable, but requires extended rest during treatment.

For more information about Cuddles, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet girl, please submit an application for her at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
Meet Darla, a sweet and chill gal who found herself homeless and sharing a yard with a fur friend. She was rescued from sleeping under the shed this Christmas after being attacked by some other dogs and needing vet care pretty badly. She is on antibiotics and eye ointment and will have her bum leg evaluated soon, and will be spayed as soon as she is well enough. She is getting along with other dogs and cats and is housetrained and crate trained. Because she is a courtesy post, all applications will be screened and forwarded to the current caregiver. The application is available on the rescue website and can be completed online.We work with many rescues and strive to find every rescued dog in our care a great home. Sometimes that means transferring that pet to another location where adoption may be more likely. We currently have partners in New York, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.

If you are interesting in meeting any of our pets, the process is to complete an application. It can be downloaded as a pdf document from our website and submitted by email to WindyRidgeRescue@gmail.com as a scanned document or as photos OR can be completed entirely online. Both links are in the header of our website.

Because we are foster based, we require an approved application to schedule a meet and greet. We feel that is fair to our fosters and rescues so every meet and greet can result in an adoption.

We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. The medical care for every dog can easily exceed the adoption donation. Average adoption fees for dogs in the area range from $175 up to $450.

We ask for a minimum adoption donation of $50 for cats regardless of age. Each cat is up to date on vaccinations, dewormer, and microchipped. Larger donations are always welcome so we can rescue more. Medical care for each cat easily exceeds the minimum donation.

As with every rescue, our resources are limited and the need for rescue help is unlimited. Your generosity helps us to rescue more.

Adopting or fostering for a rescue frees up a space where a new rescue can reside.

If you can't adopt or foster, than please consider donating.

animal.description:
Jayson Stark is a hunky 3-year-old beefcake who was confiscated from a cruelty situation in Tennessee. Lucky for us (and for him!) a wonderful PFP volunteer flew down to pick up Jayson, his companion Hazel Mae, and their surviving puppies from the shelter. Once Jayson hopped on that plane, he never looked back! 

Now he is learning to live in a house with other dogs, but he needs to be on crate rest due to heartworm treatment, so he doesn't get to play as much as he’d like. Happily, he still gets cuddle time on the couch with his foster parents and four-legged foster sisters, and that's enough for him. Thankfully for all involved, Jayson is a doll in his crate and he only whines when he needs to potty or get a drink of water!
 
Jayson has also never met a stranger. Every person he meets, he warms up to immediately and sits by them looking for pets. From hopping on a plane with one stranger to going to a new place with two new people and dogs to snuggle with, Jayson is absolutely fearless! When you first look at him, you will see his handsome strength. Once you get to know him though, you'll notice his floppy feet and the goofy smile that comes out when he gets cuddles! 

Another fun fact: he loves peanut butter bones! He gets one every day in his crate while winding down for the evening, and he definitely knows when it is time for one, because he goes right to his crate to wait for it!

If you’ve got room in your heart and home for a big lug like Jayson, fill out a survey at https://www.playersforpits.com/adoption-survey.

animal.description:
Meet Mambo!

Mambo is a handsome Husky/Malamute Mix, who just turned 1yr old. He is about 65 lbs and growing. He loves meeting new people and will do best with dogs his size or larger. Mambo will need a tall fenced yard to run around and tire himself out. He is full of energy and can walk for miles. He will make a great jogging partner or fetching friend for an active owner. He is crate trained and mostly house trained. He LOVES car rides and playing in the snow. 

Puppies have special needs and require a home where there will be someone available to care for, socialize, and train them during the day. If your family is away from the home for several hours at a time, please consider adopting a teenager or adult dog.

Our standard adoption fees are as follows $400 for puppies up to 12 months, $300 for adults, and $200 for seniors 7yrs and up with cash or check. It includes spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations, fecal testing, deworming, flea and tick preventative, heartworm preventative, free vet visit at one of our participating vets, and micro-chipping.

We must have an application, conduct a phone interview, and meet your entire family to approve an adoption. Please visit www.rescuedrascalsil.org for an application. 

Please note that the breeds and sizes posted in this biography are educated best guesses and are not guaranteed.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting our first step is our adoption application, located on our website. After submitting someone will be in contact with you soon! 
Hi! My name is Indy and I’m a three and a half year old Australian Shepherd. I am red Merle in color and weigh about 63 pounds. I have been told that I’m a very handsome boy. I am house trained and crate trained and I love to play. My rescue had me checked out at the vet because one of my rear paws drags a bit when I run or walk. Luckily the vet said it was an old injury that had healed wrong and would not require surgery. It doesn’t hurt me but my new owners should keep an eye on it as I age. This doesn’t limit my activities as I love going on walks and chasing my fur sister around the yard. My foster mom makes sure I walk on the grass so my foot doesn’t get irritated from the concrete sidewalk. We are going to try a boot too and see if I like that. One thing I want to mention is that I am very fearful of strangers and need time to get to know you and trust you. I need someone who will be patient with me and understand my needs. Once we establish a mutual trust, I am a very loyal companion. I am happy laying by your side and will rest my head in your lap for some pats and ear rubs. My ideal home would be a quiet environment with not a lot of people coming and going. I must have a fur sister or brother as I love other dogs and need them to build my confidence. I am being fostered in Allen, Texas and would love to meet you soon!! 
Adoption Fee: $350
Application REQUIRED!

animal.description:
Bo is a 7 lb. 10 yr old Mini Apricot Poodle who was released to HEART from a puppy mill on Dec. 14, 2020. 
He needs a quiet understanding home with at least one other small (social) dog and no small children. He is NOT aggressive at all, he just has trauma in his past and is initially afraid of human touch. A fenced yard would be preferred, but not required.
Bo likes to have a safe place with a warm soft bed. He is very tolerant of anything that needs to be done with him, but will walk away when needing to go pick him up. He LOVES other little dogs and has recently started to take interest in bones and toys. He is not potty trained, but will go potty quickly when going outside in fenced yard. He does not do any leg lift marking and typically waits until he is taken outside to potty. He sleeps in a pen vs. a kennel and enjoys spending time in his pen. As time goes by, he has been navigating around the house with more confidence. 
Bo has an old femoral neck injury that causes decreased mobility in his back leg and probable arthritis. He can walk on all four legs, but does lift his back leg up at times. His bloodwork was good and his vet work is complete. 
If you meet his needs and are interested in adopting Bo, you can submit an application at www.heartrescueteam.com

animal.description:
Note: While Basenji's are known to be barkless and hypoallergenic, Peter Pan is not.

Hi! I'm Peter Pan, my story begins when I was sent away to Neverland (the shelter) it was a scary awful place but luckily I was rescued and taken out of that place. After spending time on the other side I became fearful and really unsure of people and afraid that they would send me back to that awful place. I tried to be as scary as I could in hopes people would keep their distance. I LOVED my foster family though! Apparently what I was doing wasn't proper puppy behavior so I was sent to this AMAZING guy who helped me trust people. We have played, laughed, cuddled and played some more. Apparently we did something called "training" too but I don't know what that is. I have learned some amazing things like sit, stay, come and how to walk on a leash; apparently pulling is frowned upon, who knew. I'm now looking for my forever family. One that will take me on awesome adventures exploring this amazing land, no terrain is too hard for Peter Pan! I sometimes like to be bossy, it's in my DNA - what can I say? I really need a person who will be a strong leader and keep me in line. I like small children from afar but not up close, I like my kids to be older. I have not been officially cat tested but I'm sure that I would be way too interested in them, therefore a home with cats would not be a good fit for me. I would really like to end my story with a happily ever after... could it be with you?

If you are interested in giving Peter Pan the home that he needs and deserves, please fill out an adoption application at lastdaydogs.com

Note: While Basenji's are known to be barkless and hypoallergenic, Peter Pan is not.

animal.description:
This is Gunther, a 3 year old Chihuahua mix.
He is new to our rescue so we are still working on his potty training.
He is good in a crate and he gets along with other dogs.
He likes his buddies to leave his food alone so he should be fed separately from other animals. Many dogs who have been out on their own have what we call food aggression. 
He is a cute little bugger, and not a barker.

He looks like he could be what we call a Chi-Weenie. Looks like he weighs about 15 pounds. Very jaunty.

Filling out an application is the first step in the adoption process. If you have questions, the best way to contact us is to email azdesertrottis@aol.com.

We don't always bring all animals to our adoption events so check ahead of time to make sure the animal you are interested in is still available. Some animals listed may already be promised.

Arizona Desert Rotti & Pals Rescue is a NO KILL rescue serving Tucson and the surrounding area. 

We do adopt out of area under the right circumstances. If you are willing to travel to Tucson to meet us, and to personally transport your adopted pet home, we may be willing to work with you. 

A home visit is usually required for the safety of our animals. We check the yard to make sure this little pup cannot escape, no predator can get in, and also look for hazardous plants. 

We do not adopt our dogs out unless you have a fenced yard, it’s a requirement for the safety of the dog. At the end of the application, please include the type of fencing and the height of the fence you have around your yard. 

If you're interested in Saxon or any of our dogs, please fill out a pre application at: http://www.azdesertrotti.com/html/to_adopt.htm
Once you have filled out the pre-adoption application, someone will contact you about the dog to answer your questions and tell you where our Sunday adoption event is held.

Our dogs are bathed, dewormed, vet checked, given their required shots, spayed or neutered, and microchipped. 

Our rescues are homed with foster parents. They are fostered in homes so that we can tell you a little bit about their personalities, feeding schedule, habits, behavior, whether they get along with other dogs. We can tell you if they are crate trained, if they are leash trained and house trained. Most dogs need a refresher course on potty training when they go to a new home. They need to learn your routine, and it will be up to you to teach them. 

Even the most abused animals can be wonderful pets. It takes patience, love and good food, along with fun and commitment to the animal. Fosters work with these animals. They are a part of our families, while we are lucky enough to have them.

animal.description:
******PLEASE CONSIDER SPONSORING MACHO TO HELP US GET HIM HEALTHY ENOUGH TO EVENTUALLY FIND HIS HAPPILY EVER AFTER FOREVER HOME*****
By looking at this little guy's body – it is immediately clear: This poor boy has been neglected, and he has been for far too long. This does not happen overnight, no. It took months to get this point; to where poor Macho is now in such shockingly ghastly condition. But he has suffered, each and every step of the way. It is unacceptable, and to be quite honest, downright appalling – regardless of just what underlying condition(s) he may be up against. Macho's condition is completely and wholly unacceptable. 

Macho is a senior gentlemen, who has lived with one family, and one family alone – his entire life. He has looked up to – and relied on – a select few people, who he believed truly cared for him. But then, Macho found himself on the side of the road, alone. He was a little man in a very big world; scared, and undoubtedly confused. Where was his family? Where were his humans? Did he do something bad - something that maybe changed their minds about him?

No matter how you slice his cake, this baby boy's outcome was not fair. And it definitely wasn't right. Macho is loyal; Macho loves unconditionally. But despite giving his humans all he had to give (and then some), this beautiful soul found himself very scared, and very alone. He couldn't figure out what he'd done to deserve this. – He didn’t mean to grow old. But thankfully, however, Macho's fate changed, when Rusty Rover Canine Rescue came across his photo on a local shelter's website. And immediately, they knew he needed out.  We knew we were his only chance at a second chance. We knew there was so much more going on with this little guy and he needed our help. 

Now, Macho SAFE with rescuers of Rusty Rover Canine Rescue. But the neglect this poor boy has faced is overwhelmingly blatant; he is terrified, and so, so weak. He is severely emaciated, down to nothing but skin and bones. And most recently, diagnostic tests have revealed this poor boy is Diabetic – which, up until this point, has not been regulated by any means. And to add to his ever-growing list – poor Macho has also developed an aggressive form of dental disease; he suffers from a heart murmur; he has cataracts and visual impairments in his eyes; and he is so, so emaciated. Macho is - to put it bluntly - utterly and wholly heartbreaking. 

Macho needs follow up with a regular vet to get his diabetes regulated; and beyond this, Macho needs help with lifelong management. (Insulin injections twice a day, along with regular glucose checks to make sure his insulin is working correctly, and also a special diet). He also needs internal medicine and cardiology consultations as he at be hypothyroid and has a heart murmur. This little guy has been through the wringer. He has a long road to recovery ahead of him, but thankfully, he is now in the best hands capable of taking on the task. Rescuers are committed and ready for the long haul – because they know, and we know, that Macho more than deserves the medical and emotional help he needs to get back on all four paws. 

Please keep this special boy in your thoughts and prayers, and if you are able to assist with Macho's care, please consider donating to this fundraiser. If you can, please consider donating to support this baby's ongoing care today and help give him the second chance he deserves; any donation, no matter the size, means the world to both rescuers, and to Macho. – Because together, we can all make sure we get more of Macho to love! Thank you all, for your kindness and support!

animal.description:
**Please read thoroughly before applying to adopt Cooper**

Cooper is a young guy who is full of spunk! It is clear that he did not have any training of any kind before he came to Adopt A Husky and was quite the wild child. He did not know how to play with other dogs, although he wanted to, and he was so jumpy and mouthy that it was hard for people to work with him. Thankfully, we were able to call in the professionals, and he got to go to school at Bark University! He has now learned how to play appropriately with other dogs and has learned a bit of impulse control. He is incredibly sweet and loving, gentle with adults, and has learned how to relax when it is time to do so - as long as he has had some exercise.

Cooper has come a long way with his training, but he still gets a bit mouthy and jumpy at times. When he gets overstimulated or overexcited, he may forget his manners. He will not do well on a tie-out, so any fence must be 6-feet high. He will sail right over anything lower. He is super smart and seeks adventure, so he will need constant supervision when outside.

Cooper's perfect home does not have kids under age 13, has at least one adult who will keep him active with lots of walks, running, biking, or participating in dog powered sports. He also needs humans who understand that his training needs to be worked on daily and will give him treats for being a good boy - he will work for food! Cooper would love another young, active dog in the home to play with as long as they like to play rough and play, play, play! He is not dominant or bossy, and takes corrections well from other dogs, but would be way too much for a senior dog or a small dog.

Cooper would prefer to continue working with his trainers at Bark University in Mundelein, Illinois and would love to continue going to daycare regularly. We will require his adopters to complete at least a few training sessions at Bark University, so you need to live close to Mundelein, and continue training with a positive reinforcement trainer.

If you have Siberian experience and are looking for an active boy to keep you on your toes, apply for Cooper now!

animal.description:
Local Adopters Only
- Metro Atlanta Only - No Exceptions

Please read carefully and only inquire if you meet the requirements below. We will not make exceptions.

- Tyler must be the only pet in the home.
- Tyler needs a tall wood 6ft privacy fence, no short chain link fences 4 ft tall

- No children in the home, if kids visit it must not be often as Tyler is not used to kids and was previously abused and has trust issues. Tyler is a beautiful dog, but PLEASE don't inquire because he's handsome.

- He needs a person very experienced with dogs!!!

- Tyler does best with women and has only lived with women. He's met 2 men ever in his life that he trusted. He will not be adopted to a home with only a man, there must be a woman in the home.

- Age range for adopter is 40-60. No older, no younger please. He's still an active dog and we doing our best to match his energy level with the right person.

Tyler is a darling boy but a very special dog with specific needs. Please read his description and only inquire if you meet the requirements below and are serious about helping a dog with special needs and behavior issues.

Tyler is a 6 year old, male, Terrier/Poodle mix, and weighs around 30 lbs. He's a gorgeous boy and is very loving once he gets to know and trust you. Tyler needs extra time to get used to new people and will do best after a few introductions. He was very scared when we first got him and he didn't trust anyone. A trainer said he was previously abused which makes sense why it takes time for him to become comfortable with new people.

He loves our volunteers, who he knows and trusts. He needs a calm, loving person and home, and someone with a lot of dog experience. He doesn't like strangers coming up to him until he gets to know them well. He must have the right adopter and right home for this to work out. He will do best in a very calm, quiet home with someone who will be patient until he comes out of his shell. An apartment will not work. Not a home with much company or out of town visitors either. Preferably a one or two person home with no children or grandchildren. Tyler is not used to small kids at all.
If someone will give him a chance, they will be very happy they did. He's one of the most loving dogs ever and even likes to give hugs around your neck!
Tyler loves to play with toys and to go for walks and especially likes to hang out on the sofa. He rides great in the car also. He must be the only pet in the home. Other animals who get too close really seems to bother him. He has never been around children and given that he's nervous with new people at first, kids will not be suitable for him. The most important thing is a calm, quiet home with one or two people, preferably someone a little older and more settled. Young adults, out of college, engaged or who will have children in the future won't be the right match for Tyler. He's still very active so we'd like someone in the 40-60 year old age range.

In order for Tyler to get used to someone new, it will take several introductions.
We've had dogs like Tyler in the past and when we take things slow, they work out beautifully for the dog and for the adopter.

Only local adopters/Metro Atlanta only - No Exceptions

animal.description:
Ginger is a 5 year old female mini lab mix. She's a perfect size, only 35 lbs, full grown with a gorgeous caramel coat.
Ginger is a sweet, very spunky girl who's still very active but also has moments of being calm and laid back. Although she's an inside dog, Ginger loves having a fenced yard where she can relax in the sun and run around safely in. She's strong on leash for her size. An active owner is best, and a person who has owned and raised dogs. Ginger is a sweet girl but can be stubborn at times. She doesn't like you to grab her collar until she's very familiar with you and has gained trust. She's good when she meets strangers, but can get very scared at the vet when she has to get shots and her nails clipped. Someone who's owned multiple dogs in the past and preferably someone who's even owned a dog with behavior issues would be a good match for Ginger.
She likes running around outside with other dogs and loves going for walks. She loves people, plays well with other dogs, but doesn't care for overly hyper dogs who jump on her.
She's never lived with small children, so a home with kids at least 12 and up would be best. Ginger is also housebroken, spayed, current on shots.

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt. After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email PlusDogs@ILDobeRescue.com. Our adoption radius is 3 hours from the Chicagoland area.

Enzoe is a 6-month-old (born around June) Heinz 57, which means he might have all sorts of breeds mixed in him. At 30 pounds now, he may weigh more than 75 lbs when full-grown. Our resident breed expert sees some possible Australian Shepherd and Rottie, but we make no guarantees. Enzoe was purchased from a rural flea market and then surrendered to a shelter when the family had second thoughts about getting a puppy. He’s safe in an IDR+ foster home, and his foster mom says that he is a pretty well-behaved puppy, considering his age. He is catching onto housebreaking. Enzoe is full of playful energy! He is a happy guy who would love to have a playmate, but the resident dogs and cats in his foster home don’t share his enthusiasm despite his friendly invitation. He can live with a dog-savvy cat and willing doggie friends. Enzoe has learned to sit for petting instead of jumping, but he sometimes gets excited and forgets. Small kids may not appreciate his excitement, so homes with kids 7 and up can be considered. If there are children in the home, he will require a fenced yard (no e-fence). He will also require an obedience commitment to ensure his success.

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.

animal.description: Do you want to adopt me? Just go to www.dogsasfamily.org and fill out an adoption application.Hi, my name is Ariel. I am a catahoula that is about 5 years old and I weigh 54 pounds. I came to the rescue after a nice lady stopped and helped me. See, I was just sitting beside the road waiting but they never came. She tried to find them but when she couldn't so I came to the rescue. I was adopted for over three years and recently returned because my person went to heaven. I need you to be my new family.I can be quiet, easy going girl sometimes but I love to run and play too. I am kind and loving to children and I want to protect my family. Nothing really upsets me unless someone tries to bother the family but I could never see myself hunting or anything like that. I am a house pet and live inside with you. Consider me a companion for you and the family. I know how to sit, stay, walk on a leash and I am crate & house trained too. I still forget what I am doing and jump up on you sometimes. I did have an accident years ago and caught my chest on a fence (no more four foot fences for me), they sewed it back closed but I have some extra skin that is hanging down. It doesn't bother me so I hope you feel the same about it. I really want to run and play with other dogs my size or maybe you want to give me extra attention.I have been spay, vaccinated and microchipped. My adoption fee is 150.00 and you can start the process by completing an application at www.dogsasfamily.org. I like you already.

animal.description:
ADOPTION DONATION FOR THIS PET: $275. ADOPTION. APPLICATIONS CAN BE FILLED OUT AT WWW.SOHODOGRESCUE.ORG.

Available!!
Batman is a sweet, energetic Sheltie / Border Collie mix who is ready for this forever home. He is 5 years old and has a long black and white coat with adorable panda markings on his face. He weighs about 52 lbs but should be about 45 - lots of walks and hiking will take care of that! Batman is house trained, crate trained, knows some obedience commands and is highly treat motivated! He likes to ride in the car and is learning to walk well on the leash.’

Batman loves people! He is a pretty high Velcro guy who wants to be with his people constantly. He loves being a part of the “action”... even if the “action” is just playing with a toy while you work at home. He enjoys long walks and hikes, and likes the company of other dogs so far though he gets so excited when he meets them that we have to remind him to take it easy. He was an “only child” prior to coming to us so is still learning to share and tends to resource-guard his food. He loves toys and will play by himself with them too - he is quite gentle and non-destructive with them. He has not been cat tested.

The ideal home for this funny, handsome guy is a family who will make him a part of the action and make this sweet pup the center of attention. He does not do well around small children, so children above the age of 12 are required. He really loves to be with his people and prefers a calmer home with lots of exercise, and does just fine walking on a leash (though he is still learning his manners). He does have some skin irritation that is currently doing much better with a commonly available, limited ingredient diet. Another dog would be okay though isn’t required. He loves to walk and run so an active person that wants a dog to join them is key, as well as someone who wants to do some training with this guy because he LOVES to learn. If Batman sounds like he was made for your home, please apply today! Batman is fostered in Washington, D.C.

June Boy
Male
Age: 1 year old
Weight: 57 lbs
Breed: Tree Walker Coonhound

Hi, I'm June Boy! I am just your average Coonhound who loves to use my sniffer to hunt and find new things! I am quite the goofball who not only has lots of energy, but equally loves to snuggle up for a good nap! My foster mom says I am extra cute when I am taking a snooze!
I have been told I am very smart! I am learning new things in my foster home such as commands like sit; tasty treats certainly help motivate me to learn! I am still working on my house training skills, but I think with enough patience along with a good routine, Ill be a master at that in no time! I also do very well in my crate and will sleep in my crate throughout the night. I am also getting really good at walking on a leash and would love a walking/running companion of my very own! I get along with other dogs very well and enjoy a good play session! I am still learning which toys belong to me and will need a family to teach me what a true chew toy is all about; perhaps a good furry sibling role model will help teach me the ways
I will require an active family who is ready to give me all the love including lots of walks and/or runs around the neighborhood. I will also require a fenced in backyard that is tall and sturdy allowing me to run around and safely chase those neighborhood squirrels!

I have met kitty cats and have gotten very excited around them and think I will do well with them over time.

If you are interested in meeting the goofy June Boy, apply to adopt at www.causeforcanines.org Adoption fee: $250
Children must be 5 years old or older
Must be an Ohio resident 25 years old or older

animal.description:
Application link: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/4411/generic
Name: Rover 
Breed: German Shepherd 
Age: 8 years D.O.B 7/5/12
Gender: Male 
Location: Dixon KY 
Adoption fee: Adoption fee is $55 includes bordetella vaccination, Rabies vaccination, DHPP vaccination, fecal, heartworm check, heartworm treatment, monthly prevention's, microchip (includes lifetime membership), neuter! 

We do require an approved application at this time to set up a meet and greet. 

PLEASE READ BIO BEFORE APPLYING! Meet Rover, some of you might remember his previous information about how bad of shape he was in when we got him back. As you can see hes looking great now. Hes gained weight and his hair is back. Rover cant seem to catch a break though from his past, as he is heartworm positive (hes undergoing treatment), has hip dysplasia, and he has neuropathy in his front leg. With all that though comes the most upbeat sweetest dog youll find around. Rover loves other dogs, kids, adults, and even doesnt mind dog savvy cats. We are looking for a special home for Rover. He will need to be continued on his joint supplement for life, and further down the road might require more medical. He deserves to be in a home living the good life. Rover still needs to get his exercise to keep his front leg strengthened, but not over do it. He tries his best to keep his kennel clean, so we believe hell easily catch on to being housebroken. 

Keep up with us, our events, our adoptable animals, etc on our Facebook page under Mollys Mutts Animal Rescue! You can also view our adoptable pets on https://www.petstablished.com/organization/95250 Follow us on Instagram and Twitter under mollysmuttsanimalrescue 
Please call us at 270-318-4177, email us mollysmuttsanimalrescue@yahoo.com or private message us with questions!

animal.description:
CHIP CHIP HOORAY!! Hi everyone! This fellas name is Chip. He’s a 2 and half year old Catahoula mix.
He came to us via the New Iberia Parish shelter. He was picked up as a stray, but we think he once had a family because he knows how to sit and shake and is very well behaved.  
He is heartworm positive but has already started treatment! We are working on his house training and he's doing great. He has also picked up on the kennel training quite fast. 
He gets along great with the other three dogs at his foster’s home! He LOVES LOVES to be outside. He walks well on a leash and enjoys his twice daily walks. He is about 40lbs and would make a great addition to anyone's family.

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
Hunter was found running loose on a property and taken to the San Martin Shelter. No one came looking for this sweet little 2 year old boy. Hunter is initially shy and nervous around new people, loud noises and sudden movements but he so wants to part of the group. At this time he is scared to go for walks on leash but give him time. He is good with other small dogs who show him that things that scare him, are really safe. He is really sweet natured and is really full of young dog energy and playfulness. Hunter has been neutered and is current with his vaccinations. At this time, he is best with another friendly dog he can play with and who can show him "the ropes" and a family with the patience to let Hunter get to know them slowly!! He is a doll and so worth the effort! Is yours the family for Hunter?

Please note:
- Hunter would do best as an only child
- Hunter is shy and needs a quiet home
- Hunter is nervous around men
- Needs a securely fenced yard

For more information or to apply for Hunter, please go to:
http://www.companionsinwaiting.org/iams/../adopt/dog.php?id=1610

animal.description:
Meet Roxy!

Roxy is 8 years old and weighs 60 lbs. She is definitely the most affectionate girl, who loves being around her people. Roxy loves her smaller, foster sister dog and knows how to share toys while still being nice. She isn't a big fan of larger dogs, but would do well with others her size and smaller. She absolutely loves getting pets and affection any chance she can get. Roxy sleeps soundly in her crate through the night, it is her safe space where she unwinds after a long day. She loves being in the presence of her family, so she would prefer it if you gave her a little corner in your bedroom to spend the night. Roxy's day begins with potty time and a bit of exercise around the yard. Breakfast time is her favorite, (who doesn't love food?) and she will patiently sit and wait for you to prep her bowl, however, she is still working on the sitting part. She is super gentle when taking food off your fingers such as training treats or a tasty piece of dog biscuits. Roxy will be a great companion for someone who likes to enjoy life's quiet moments. When her foster parents are relaxing on the couch, Roxy loves to lay on a soft blanket and nap next to them. She is uninterested in having feline friends, so it would be best to stick to canine or human brothers and/or sisters. Roxy is very respectful of everything inside the home and is not interested in chewing anything up, making her the perfect inside dog. Because of her age, Roxy tends to walk a little slower than younger dogs, but that doesn't mean she won't enjoy a nice walk in the park with her family, and she's great on a leash! She's the perfect representation of a gentle dog and deserves to be spoiled through her best years in a loving home!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
Meet Sharkey & Hunter!  This bonded pair of German Shepherd's are looking for a loving forever home. 

Sharkey is a very mellow, loveable boy!?  He knows all basic commands and is well mannered.  Sharkey loves his belly rubs and pets.  Sharkey does have some allergies and tends to bite and lick causing sores or missing patches of skin. He needs a medicated bath 2-3 x week. Medicated spray on sore patches as well as benadryl a few times a day.  ?He loves to play ball and tends to keep it when you think you're playing fetch.?Sharkey will go to everyone, adults and children alike. He will bark if he sees a stranger in the yard and can be very protective of his family. 

Hunter is the opposite of Sharkey. He is hyper and happy all the time.? Hunter was a rescue and he is timid when people come over. You have to leave him alone and give him time so he knows you're okay, then he warms up.  He is very protective of his family and will let you know if something doesn't feel right to him. Hunter loves when you pet him and belly rubs are his absolute favorite. He loves to give kisses and be affectionate. ?Hunter loves to play with all of his toys, and takes them all out of the toy box.? He knows all the basic commands and is house trained.

Both boys are extremely loving and truly love one another.  We really want to keep them together.  Both are neutered and up to date on vaccines.  For additional info or to meet them, please text 702-239-7986.  MUST HAVE EXSPERIENCE

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Lambeau! My foster mom calls me La-La-Lambeau and sometimes she sings it even though she is a terrible singer. I am loving life in my foster home. I love going for car rides, hanging out with the other dogs, and supervising the cat. Speaking of cats, I am curious about him and will chase him if he runs, but my interest is harmless. He's just really, really interesting. There is a teenager in my foster home. She mostly stays in her bedroom doing teenager-y things, but I like hanging out with her when she emerges. I would be fine with kids of any age. My foster parents work from home, which is great because I have a bit of separation anxiety. My foster mom says that my foster dad is welcome to go back to his regular office building any day now, but that's a whole other story. I'm hoping my next home will also contain people who are around a lot. Having another dog in the home is a must. I would be very unhappy as an only dog, which is partly why I was surrendered. My former family felt like I needed to be around other dog(s). I need more time and attention than they are able to provide at this time. 
I'm fairly petite so if you're in the market for a diminutive Boxer lass, I'm your girl. I'm playful and energetic, but I'm also down with a nap or a Netflix bingefest. My foster mom says I'm very easy to have around. She says I fit right in and barely needed any adjustment time. As much as I love living in my foster home, I know that it will soon be time for me to have a new home of my very own.

Please fill out application for Lambeau here: https://www.greenacresboxerrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Meet Cupcake!

Hello everyone, my name is Cupcake! I'm about 7 years old and 65 pounds. I'm an older lady now, so my legs don't have the strength they once did and now they are a bit wobbly. I can't do stairs anymore. I do a really good job at going outside to go potty, and I enjoy short walks since my legs tire easily or just cruising in the backyard. I'm an easy girl and don't ask for much just a family to love me. I need a family where I can be their one and only, the apple of their eye, the peanut butter to their jelly, the....oh, you get it! Other dogs cause me to feel on edge and after an injury to my tail that required it to be docked, I would enjoy a home where I am not around other dogs so I can relax and enjoy my golden years. I do well with kids though! I met a 2 year old little girl here and she seems pretty cool. I like her a fair bit. I also enjoy relaxing in a bed napping. With age comes more sleep they say and I'm perfectly okay with that. Do you want to know what makes me excited? Thinking about finding my new home, with my forever people, where I can live out my retirement years without any worry in the world. Do you have a quiet home where I can rest my head and get a little love?

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
Chris Webber , aka Splotch

Must have a fenced in yard and another playful dog in his forever home. As one of the FAB babies , rescued with suspected ringworm (puppies are often euthanized for that at shelters!), Chris Webber bka Splotch started life with a close call. Turned out though, it was never ringworm these poor puppies had, just a yeast infection. Once the meds started working and they began to feel better - coupled with good nutrition and the love of a foster family - the brothers all started showing their true personalities! Feisty about sums them all up!

Toys, chase, tug o'war, exploring - they love ALL the things. It's been a joy to watch this litter go from sickly little babies to playful, healthy, stinkers! Their foster family just loves them and their antics! They get along with dogs of all shapes and sizes and because they're so incredibly playful and used to having built in wrestle partners, they will require another dog in their home. They love kids and the activity level that goes along with them. When they have finally worn themselves out with all the playing, chasing, and just plain being adorable, they do love a good snuggle sesh. They're the total package!

We suspect they will stay small to medium since they're all around 10 pounds and 17ish weeks at this point. We're guessing they are chihuahua/heeler mixes.

If you have a spot in your home for one of these boys, their big personalities, and their larger than life ears, submit an application @maxxandme.org

Chris Webber is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. His adoption donation is only $300! As with all puppies adopted through Maxx & Me, his adopter will need to commit to continue working with a positive reinforcement trainer of their choice to help him continue to become a well mannered and confident boy.

To meet any of our dogs please fill out an application on www.maxxandme.org.

Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

Turned out though, it was never ringworm these poor puppies had, just a yeast infection. Once the meds started working and they began to feel better - coupled with good nutrition and the love of a foster family - the brothers all started showing their true personalities! animal.description:
Candy Litter 2020Updated: 1/26/2021
Litter Name: Candy Litter 2020
Born: 10/31/2020
Hi, I'm Hershey! I'm a young energetic terrier mix. My Mom is a 12 lbs Black/White Terrier mix but I don't know my Dad. I'm going thru a growing spurt right now, weighing in at about 15 lbs. If you like to go for exercise in the morning, I'm your jogging pal. With the cold and the snow I get the 'morning zoomies' before I settle down for a nap. Clear your lap, here I come! Housebreaking has taken a step back, but with time and patience, we can do it! I sleep thru the night in my crate and make playing with toys my priority. Sitting for my treat when I come in from doing my business outside and trying to learn new commands is easy. Snuggling and watching TV with you is on my wish list. I want to please you and find my furever home with a family of my own. Fill out an application and get to know me with the 5 day Foster to Adopt program!
Adoption Fee: $500.00
We are a Wisconsin state licensed dog rescue -WI# 402433

***We do not have a central adoption center at this time. All our dogs are in private foster homes within WI. At this time we only place our dogs in areas of WI. The breed of our dogs is our best guess with the help of our veterinarians.
Our Weight Classes are as follows:
0- 25lbs - Small
26- 45lbs - Medium
46-89 - Large
90+ X-large
If you are adopting an adult dog, which we consider 6 months of age or older, your adoption fee includes the following:
Spay/Neuter, Rabies and Distemper shots, dewormed, flea & tick preventative, heartworm tested and microchipped.
If you are adopting a dog younger than 6 months of age, the dog will be up to date on the shots as per the dogs age. The dog will be dewormed, flea/tick preventative and microchipped. We only spay/neuter our dogs by 6 months of age. If you decide to adopt a younger dog than 6 months of age, they will need to be spayed/neutered at one of our preferred clinics. This will be determined by your contract along with the month they should have their surgery. This is included in your adoption fee.
Once you are approved with our rescue, you can meet any one of our dogs within the fosters home. If you are interested in the dog you met, you can take the dog home under our mandatory foster to adopt program. You receive 5 days to see if the dog is the right fit for your home.
If it is, we will conduct the home visit and finalize adoption. If it is not, it is returned to the foster. We are happy to find you another dog that meets your needs in your home.
If a dog is listed as PENDING, a family has met the dog and planning on adopting the dog after the home visit has been conducted. We always suggest sending in an application for a dog because there are times where the dogs are given back to us under the foster to adopt program. There are many reasons dogs are returned but normally it just was not the right fit for all.Please go to WWW.TAILWAGGERS911.COM under HOW TO ADOPT . We have an online application that is very easy to fill out.

animal.description:
This is Nick, a nine-year-old American Bulldog who needs a new home.  With heavy hearts his owners have decided to rehome him.  They took Nick in as a foster in 2017 and adopted him in 2018. They worked with him to curtail his jumping up on and nipping people when they entered the house. He does so much better now and has come a long way since he was rescued from an abusive and neglectful situation when he was four years old.
            Unfortunately, this couple, who are in their mid-60s, have suffered serious declines in their health the last couple of years and they find that Nick is simply too much for them due to his size (70 pounds) and energy.
Nick loves people and loves any positive attention they bestow on him. He does well on a leash and loves to go for walks.  He loves his toys and spends a lot of time chewing on them. He is house trained, crate trained, neutered and heart-worm free. He had his annual physical in October 2020 and is up-to-date on his shots.
Nick has not been around children, but because of his size and excitability it is highly recommend that there be no small children in the home. Older teens, not small for their age, should be fine.
He is NOT aggressive and does not try to dominate other dogs, but will defend himself if another large dog shows aggression toward him. Because of this, Nick should only go to a home with no other dogs, or at the most with no other large dogs. With his current family, he has been snapped at and bitten by their 14-year-old, 16-lb Parsons terrier. When that happens, Nick heads for the other side of the room and stays away from the terrier for a while. He has not been around cats so it is not known how he would react to them.
Nick is located in the mid-Florida area.  His owners will work to arrange transportation for distances over 100 miles, including out of state, to the right home or rescue.
If you are interested in adopting Nick, please fill out an application at http://www.betterlifepets.com/
For more information, please contact jkosmensky@yahoo.com or call Jill at 863-325-6964.

animal.description:
Meet Esther Elizabeth. She is FOR SURE a Hound Dog -including the digging and barking and snuggling! Once a tiny, very sick puppy, Esther (AKA "PupPup") is now a healthy and growing hound pup. She's gone from a 4 pounds, 5 week old baby with suspected ringworm (it was actually a very severe case of pyoderma) to a 21 pound, 16 week old juvenile. When we first rescued her, her hair would fall off in clumps every time you touched her. She maxed out at about 40% hair loss and has since grown it all back. Scars remain on her chest and legs and around her body where the infection was just so deep but they're just a testament to her past and the resiliency it took to over come. At five weeks old, she was found in a drainage ditch. Cold, wet, COVERED in scabs and already missing a big portion of her hair, the shelter pleaded for a rescue to step in and help this sick, scared baby. We jumped at the chance!

In the time we have had her, we have watched her blossom into a confident and playful, social and loving dog. Esther will require a large yard with a minimum of 6' fence. It will also need to be DIG PROOF. She will need a pack to join - not just another dog- and would love a mix of small and big, young and playful dogs. She plays with EVERY BODY and goes from one to the next wrestling and romping and then crashes in a heap. She adores children. She absolutely MUST sleep with you and wants to be touching you anytime you're sitting in close proximity. She's beyond sweet, loves being held when she's sleepy, plays rough and tumble, runs like a cantering horse, jumps like she has springs in her legs, and barks.... a lot! PupPup even talks when she stretches, including while she's sleeping! We adore this dog and tell her all the time she's lucky she's so incredibly adorable and sweet as pie since she also chews ... all the things.

Esther is spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Her adoption donation is only $300! As with all puppies adopted through Maxx & Me, her adopter will need to commit to continue working with a positive reinforcement trainer of their choice to help her continue to become a well mannered and confident girl.

To meet any of our dogs please fill out an application on www.maxxandme.org.

Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.
