Sevan is a female Australian shepherd mix with an estimated DOB of 11/30/2019. Sevan weighed 38.2 lbs at intake. She came to us as a stray. She loves playing outside and cuddling, Even though she is a bit undersocialized she enjoys the company of other dogs. She likes to play this game with the kennel staff where she will push her toys out of her area and wait for someone to come and throw it back to her.  Sevan's adoption fee is $190 which includes a medical exam, sterilization surgery, age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormer, heartworm testing, and a microchip. 

Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. As we get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

Our animals change daily, so please check our lists of adoptable dogs and adoptable cats frequently. Once you find an animal you’d like to adopt, the next steps are to complete an application and request a meet and greet with the foster. Make sure to be thorough and help us understand why you’re interested in that particular animal — and why your home is a great fit. Based on your answers we may even have a better fit for you.

All PPAS dogs are up to date on all of their vaccines (including rabies if age appropriate), and will be microchipped and registered in the adopter's name at the time of adoption. Adopters get a free consultation at an area vet partner within 14 days of adoption. Any dog that is six months of age or older will be tested for Heartworms and if found negative, will be kept on Heartworm prevention during their shelter stay, after the adoption it is up to the adopter to continue the highly recommended Heartworm preventative treatment. Also all PPAS shelter dogs are treated with a monthly topical flea/tick preventative and we ask that adopters continue that treatment as well.  All dogs and cats per state law are sterilized before they begin their new fabulous lives with their new families.

Adoption fees: Adoption fees must be paid in full at time of adoption – no partial payments are accepted. All major credit cards are accepted. Adoption fees vary. Please note if you live in the city of Ottawa a dog license fee must also be paid at time of adoption. Annual renewal of dog licenses is required between January 1st and February 15th.

Taking your animal home: The State of Kansas requires that all cats and dogs must be sterilized (spayed/neutered) before going to their new homes. In most cases animals will have already been sterilized before being placed on the adoption floor and you will be able to take your new companion home with you the day of adoption. However, if the animal is not yet sterilized, they will need to stay at the shelter and we will schedule the surgery on the next available date (usually within a week). We do request that all dogs go home with a collar/leash.

If you are interested in this pet, please either email Prairie Paws Animal Shelter at info@prairiepaws.org, for an application or visit our website @ prairiepaws.org for more information.

Chance is a big goofy mutt! He came into our vet clinic and could barely walk. His owners had a lot of health issues and he got to spend most of his days in a cage. His owners signed him over to us and he has been recovering since. He’s an amazing boy! Always happy and a little loud.

Chance is not housebroken, but I think he’s a smart boy and could pick it up quickly. He is very high energy. When I say he is happy 100% of the time he is just that. Chance has barrier frustration and we are pretty sure dog aggressive but we have not put him in a situation to test if he is just aggressive because of the cage. He loves everyone at our clinic. He gets so excited every single day to see us. He needs a home that will love him and care for him and give him the “Chance” he deserves.
It is unknown how he is with children. He is rambunctious so smaller children may not be a good choice for him.

MEET VIOLET!!!!

It's me Violet I'm so excited I wanted to share with you my special day with my volunteer friend, please read about our day together.

Her smile is contagious! Her love for her human beings is unconditional! Her beauty goes beyond skin deep!

Sometimes you meet a girl and you just know that you've become a better person for the new friend you've brought into your life. Violet is one of those girls.

She is only 2 years old and has a lifetime of love to share with a very lucky family.

During our day together I learned that Violet is a medium energy girl who enjoys a trail walk by the side of her friend.

She enjoys exploring, she will dip her toes into the water to cool off, she is intrigued by large cranes taking flight, she's a big believer in public show of affection and she loves car rides. One of the highlights of her day was when a nice lady pulled up next to us and told her how pretty she was, her bottom just wiggled all over.

Violet is looking to be your one and only. Guaranteed, with her in your life, you will never be short on love or smiles.

She will flourish in a home where she will be included as family and have people in her life dedicated to her continued success as she continues to become the best girl she knows she can be.

Here's some other info about me:

Violet is a vibrant 2yr old is described as a "Total Lovebug" She's a friendly girl that prefers not share the attention of her humans with other pets. NO OTHER PETS!!!!!! She loves Kids (older kids recommended) as she can be a bit jumpy sometimes.

Violet has such a happy outlook and just wants to have fun! She is up for walks, hikes, or a good game of fetch in the backyard! She is great in the car, and is just waiting for her new forever family. Violet enjoys going on hikes, she was such a good girl, medium energy, eager to please. She's amazing!!!! Don't wait to meet this sweet heart!!

animal.description:
Faith is an about 1-2 year old, 40 pound pit mix looking for a foster home (she is in temp foster but there are a lot of dogs there and she needs a quiet home to heal in). Her story is very sad. She was found roaming the streets very pregnant in a not so great part of town and it took weeks to catch her. She had her babies 24 hours after getting to her foster home but all the babies were still born or died at the ER vet. Faith was malnourished and had no prenatal care so it would have taken a miracle for the babies to live and they did not.
Faith is a shy girl and needs a quiet foster/adoptive home that is experienced with scared dogs and will continue to work with her to slowly gain her confidence. She has not been dog/cat tested yet since she's had so much recent trauma. She loves comfy blankets/beds and cuddles. She needs a secure 6' fenced in yard since she's a flight risk and no kids just to be safe.
Applications can be found @ maxxandme.org
Faith will be spayed (very recently postpartum), up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Her adoption donation is only $250!
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
Rowan ACCT-A-80339

Personality: Rowan may not understand personal space, but he's definitely the best cuddler around! This sweetheart is full of love and energy. Rowan loves to play, but is also just as happy being your little spoon! 

This sweet boy loves other dogs, and may whimper like a baby if you don't allow him to say hi on walks. Rowan is nervous around strangers and takes some time to warm up. But once he trusts you, he has nothing but love to give! And he may collapse onto you from time to time for a quick nap as he believes he's about 20 lbs. 

Rowan's foster recommends a family with children over 12, as he still has some learning to do and believes he's smaller than he is. But he is one very special boy who would love to be adopted into a family who is willing to train him, play with him, and give him all of the love he deserves. You can reach Rowan's foster family at mfw26@icloud.com!

Videos: 
https://youtu.be/0UHjPpEFY0s
https://youtu.be/AWOAplo9Lvs

Intake Reason: 12/3 Found Stray
Sex: Male
Age: 11 months
Altered: No

**VIDEO**
Heath and Rowan https://youtu.be/CW50mRAAL18

Medical Observations: 
12/11 (Vet Check) -- Patient remains calm and will likely benefit from Trazodone extension.
12/8 (Per Staff) -- Attempted to remove from kennel for full evaluation but unable to remove due to behavior. On approach, Rowan is growling and stiff at front of kennel. As assessor approaches, he is whale eyed and hard barking while urinating. Today, he has no interest in treats or Fresh Pet and remains tense throughout entire interaction. Able to leash with a loose loop but refuses to exit kennel and then lunges at handler who has to close kennel door with leash still on Rowan. Left kennel and returned a few minutes later and was able to remove leash while Rowan remained tense and growling.
12/7 (Per Vet) -- BAR; nervous
12/7 (Per Staff) -- Was checked in this morning. Unable to perform full evaluation but was able to remove Rowan from kennel.
12/7 (Intake Exam) -- Left eye red

Behavior Observation:
12/13 (Per Staff)-- He was quiet in the kennel, and easily leashed. He walked outside the building and sniffed surrounding. When we first approached the group he focused on another dog, but was easily distracted by changing direction. A male handler approached slowly and he hid behind my leg. Handler backed off and female handler approached, let him sniff her side, and he wagged his tail and she took him and he went for a walk and became playful. He met the male handler again and greeted him playfully. He had a dog meet with Heath through the fence, and then in the parking lot. Both were high energy and did well, play bowing and running circles around one another, and then when pulled away from Heath he stopped jumping and calmed down. He was easily put back in his kennel with no issue. 
12/10 (Per Staff)-- 
Kennel Presentation---Nervous---Took a couple of attempts to get a loop around him but otherwise stepped out easily and was returned to kennel easily with no issues.
Leash Skills---Pulls Strongly On Leash---Would do best harnessed
Handleability----Aroused/Allows all handling
Tag---Aroused---But will engage in play. Runs closely towards the handler but does not actually come into contact with them. Lots of zooms!
Toys---Accepts a trade----Trades toy for toy - mostly ball for ball. Shows attempts to drop ball in handler's lap but keeps mouth too close to attempt to take and toss again for him
12/11 (Per vet) -- standing calmly in kennel, no barking
12/8 (Per Staff)-- On approach, Rowan is growling and stiff at front of kennel. As assessor approaches, he is whale eyed and hard barking while urinating. Today, he has no interest in treats or Fresh Pet and remains tense throughout entire interation. Able to leash with a loose loop but refuses to exit kennel and then lunges at handler who has to close kennel door with leash still on Rowan. Left kennel and returned a few minutes later and was able to remove leash while Rowan remained tense and growling.
12/7 (Per Staff) Tense and growling on bed when handler approaches kennel door. Softens when presented with Fresh Pet and sniffs handler's hand but does not take treats from hand nor once dropped on floor. Tail is tucked but wags when presented with leash. Still tense but allows himself to be slowly leashed. Once leashed, loosens and exits kennel. Pulls moderately through building and outside. Startles and tenses at loud noises (dumpster being lifted, cars honking) and initially stays full leash length ahead of handler. In grass, approaches handler and allows slow pets to rear but quickly becomes overaroused, sniffing at handler's shoes and pant legs so handler starts walking with Rowan following but still in a state of arousal, sniffing at back of handler's pants so handler uses treats to distract. Rowan then falls into a walk alongside handler. Did not attempt further handling besides returning Rowan to kennel. Rowan went straight into kennel and allowed leash to be removed with loose body. After leash was removed, Rowan allowed pets to head and shoulders with loose body and no signs of arousal.
12/6 (Per Vet) -- Unable to remove from kennel for eval. Whale eyed, stiff and growling. No interest in treats or cheese. No reaction to leash when presented.
12/5 (Per Vet) -- Unable to check in due to behavior. Dog's tail is wagging low, but dog is growing, licking lips and giving whale eyes. 
12/3 (Per Vet) -- Dog was placed directly in kennel by KA without stopping at dog intake. Went to kennel, dog was low growling with tense body language.
12/3 (Per Finder) -- Happy, loose body language. Met 6, 5, 3 year old children and showed no aggression, was loose, relaxed, around them.

animal.description:
Guinevere is looking forward to 2021 just as much as the rest of us! She’s ready to start a new life. Guinevere had a tough start to life and came to us from a hoarding situation, with very little human contact. After two months in her foster home, she is doing much better and starting to learn that humans can be good! Guinevere, adoringly referred to as Gwen, is housebroken, leash trained and crate trained. She’s focusing on socialization and getting used to human contact. Training and commands will come next. Gwen is a low activity level gal who is happy to lounge all day in her dog bed, or in the yard, if the weather is nice. She’s looking for a quiet life, as loud noises startle her and cause her to shut down - hiding in a corner trying not to be seen. Gwen enjoys the company of the furry and feathery friends in her foster home and is doing great with the 6 cats, goats and free range chickens! Gwen gets along with other dogs but hasn’t decided if she wants to play with them yet, so an older, not-so-playful canine pal would be best for her. Gwen’s past has made her very fearful of men and boys. She does better warming up to females but needs her space and time to trust. Gwen is working hard to learn that the world, particularly men and loud noises, are not so scary. She is looking for a patient family, that will give her the time and space she needs to learn these things. Gwen is striving to overcome her emotional challenges. In 2021, she deserves a home in which her family will appreciate her for the quietly, courageous girl she is!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
75$ of Lulu's adoption fee has been sponsored!

Personality: Lulu is very people social and affectionate. She has a goofy, quirky, and bouncy personality. She is eager to please and will look to her human friends for direction. She loves to play with tennis balls and frisbees! She is also high energy and loves to go for long runs, and would love a household that can give her routine exercise to burn her energy. 

History: She arrived to the shelter as a stray. She lived in a foster home with 2 adults and 2 children. She has shown to be tentative at times with kids but can also become rowdy with them when comfortable. She is also excitable in an active, noisy home environment. Lulu would do best in a calm home environment and with an experienced family that can manage this behavior. 

Dog Skills: Lulu is uncomfortable meeting dogs and is looking for a home as the only dog in the household.

Cats Skills: We have observed reactive behavior toward cats, squirrels, birds, etc. Lulu is required to be the only animal in her future household because of this behavior. 

Leash Skills: Walks nicely on leash with the use of a front clip harness. Lulu can walk calmly on a leash but can become excited/frustrated when seeing dogs, cats, wildlife. She can become vocal, jumpy, and abruptly spins in circles. She would do best with a low traffic neighborhood.

Medical:
Lulu arrived at HSSV with a history of "spinning" when excited. When she gets excited or over stimulated she spins and circles to the right. It is very easy to get her to calm down and stop spinning with redirection and distraction. Based on her history, and a consultation with a veterinary neurologist, we believe this is a stable condition.

Ready to meet Lulu? Fill out the form to request an appointment Primary Color: Grey Secondary Color: Black Weight: 44.6lbs Age: 4yrs 4mths 3wks Animal has been Spayed

Lewis was found in the parking lot of a grocery store . Probably dumped . He is neutered , vaccinated and microchipped and thoroughly vetted !!  Lewis IS NOT good with cats or chickens so we think little dogs might not work either although that has not been tested.  Lsawllabrescue@gmail.com for an application

According to Punxsutawney Phil, we’ve got another 6 weeks of winter headed our way. What better way to embrace the cold than by adopting a new pal like Selena?

animal.description:
Animal Profile:
Bahamas is a senior terrier/chihuahua mix (best guess!) who originally joined us from Hawaii. He is estimated to be 8 years old, but we suspect he may be a little bit older than that (closer to 10+) as he has developed cataracts in his eyes. Bahamas was originally rescued from Hawaii, and joined us in Seattle almost 2 years ago. He landed a wonderful home in Seattle, but due to some very unfortunate circumstances/unexpected life changes, he is back in our care and looking for his forever home to retire to.

Foster Update: Bahamas is a gentle, sweet and shy pup looking for a special home to retire to. While quite shy and timid at first, Bahamas' personality continues to blossom by the week under the care of his foster family, who have been committed to helping his confidence grow. We have yet to meet a pup that loves his crate and special dog bed as much as this guy! He will happily, and quietly, snooze away during the work day. His crate was his favorite spot when he first arrived in foster care, but as the weeks go on - he is choosing cozy dog beds around the house instead. Bahamas will come running anytime he hears his meal being prepared - it's prety cute. He is a sucker for a delicious meal or special treat. During his first weeks in foster care, Bahamas was pretty timid on leash and kept his potty breaks short in the yard. As he continues to come out of his shell, he is slowly starting to gain his confidence in the outside world. Walks have still been shorter excursions for him, but his foster family has been able to expand his experiences by slowly increasing the distances for him. He has been polite encountering other dogs on leash, but really prefers his space when on walks. To this day, he has yet to have an accident in the home. Bahamas has lived in a home with other dogs before, and while he does not particularly engage in play or seek out their affection - he does feel at ease with another dog around and we do catch picking up cues from the resident dog. Bahamas is looking for a mellow canine companion in his forever home, one that will help him continue to come out of his shell a bit more. Bahamas' ideal home would be a quiet household with patient humans who are okay with going slow at first to help Bahamas adjust and settle in, as well as committed to help this boy continue to grow his confidence. This sweet boy very much deserves a loving home to retire to. Could that home be with you?

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $400, which includes spay/neuter, current core vaccinations - Rabies, DAPPV, Bordetella, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was rescued from euthanasia at a high-kill shelter in Hawaii and joined us from Kauai Humane Society rescue partner. This dog will be available for adoption in Seattle once evaluated.

About Foster to Adopt Program:
Fosters provide a safe landing spot for dogs transitioning from the shelter environment and help prepare the dogs for adoption. You provide the love and structure, and we take care of everything else! We cover all vet care, and drive the adoption process. Average length of foster is 2-3 weeks. Fosters do get first consideration for adoption, if desired.

Apply to foster online at www.doggoneseattle.org/foster-application

animal.description: Say hello to Sweetie! (DOB 2009). Sweetie was found stray in a country pasture in very rough shape. She was heavily matted with fleas and her eyes were crusted shut and she unable to see. The property owner who found her turned her over to us. We discovered she was microchipped. The chip company tried to contact her listed owner on her microchip but it was unfortunately a dead end. We, of course, immediately cleaned her up. We gave her Bravecto and shaved her. After a warm bath, including good ear and eye cleaning, she felt so much better!  We then took her to the vet for complete exam, vaccines and heartworm testing, which was negative! She went back to the vet for a dental cleaning, then to the eye specialist vet for an exam. She was diagnosed with severe dry eye and glaucoma in one blinded eye. The other eye has a cataract but it is thin enough so she can still see. Next, she had surgery to remove the painful blind eye. She is finally all well and ready for a home to call her own!  Phew! Miraculously, she will only need 2 drops daily to maintain her eye health and comfort. She is a sweet outgoing and friendly dog that loves treats. Her favorite thing is eating! She gets along well with other dogs. If you are interested in adopting Sweetie, please go to floridacocker.org and fill out an adoption application. For more information, please call 813-245-1833.

animal.description:
Look at this sweet boy's face and we guarantee that you will fall in love in a minute. Ezra is a 10-month-old Doberman Pinscher mix weighing around 70 pounds.  It is estimated that he will be around the 90-pound range when fully grown. 

Ezra is very high energy and he hits the ground running. He is highly intelligent and incredibly trainable but will need a knowledgeable and breed-experienced family to help him succeed. Ezra is most successful when he receives several hours of exercise on a daily basis. This includes playtime in a fenced area or in structured daycare. Ezra also loves food toys such as slow feed bowls, frozen kongs, and snuffle mats that allow him to use intelligence to reach a goal. 

Ezra is very social and playful and would do well as the apple of your eye or with an equally confident, energetic, and playful dog friend. He also does well with older, dog-savvy children but it is unknown how he would do with cats.

Ezra has mastered his crate training. He is working on his house and leash training. It will take some time but he knows that he will get help from his forever family to assist him in the process. 

This boy is a diamond in the rough with lots of potentials to be a wonderful canine companion. He will need to have the support of his family that will provide him will all the resources needed to harness his abundant energy but the result will be a loving and sweet canine companion. 

Ezra's adoption fee is $450. That includes the cost of spaying/neutering, up to date vaccinations, foster care, rescue, and transport fees. 

To get the ball rolling, head over to our Adoption Application and submit your application today. 

A Dog Star representative will contact you within 24 hours. 

To help speed up the process contact your vet and give them permission to speak with us.

If you do not get a response within 24  hours, check your spam folder.

animal.description:
SPECIAL MEDICAL CONDITION -- pulmonary stenosis, requires surgery; 4-5 years, 11 lbs, Chiweenie mix

Please welcome our special little dude Pokki. He's sweet and very much a good boy. Pokki has a heart condition called pulmonary stenosis. It does require surgery. Basically one of his valvs is closed and the surgery will open it up. Without surgery his life expectancy will not be super long. He's been fine so far in his life but as he gets older his risk of going into sudden heart failure is greater. He is not neutered due his heart condition, he is not cleared for surgery. But, his behavhiour has not been effected by this at all. He behaves very well and is tottaly house trained. He's just looking for his special adopter that can take care of his heart conditon. 

Pokki is a very mellow dude who just wants to be part of the family. He can be a little nervous at first but warms up fairly quickly with the right people. He's working on his outdoor confidence in the city. His dream home will be out of the city where he doesn't have to deal with the hussle and bussle. He's houstrained and very respectful of the home. Litle kids can stress Pokki out. But respectful and gentle teenageres would be okay. Ingrested in adotping? Please go to www.socialteesnyc.org or reach out to your point person. 

HIs Foster Mom Says: "Pokki is ready to wiggle his way into your heart and home! He's approximately 10 pounds and 4-5 years old, and just as sweet as can be. Pokki is mellow, and would happily spend the day curled up next to you on the couch or chewing his favorite bone. When he's happy, he wriggles around on his back and looks up at you like a little seal pup. Pokki's foster mom says he's just a dream - fully housebroken (does his business quickly outside and can use wee wee pads), exceptionally quiet in the apartment, sleeps peacefully in his crate, and knows "sit" and "paw." He gets along well with other dogs and children. Pokki is a homebody who gets a little nervous when it's time to go outside on the busy city street, but he is gaining confidence and just needs a little extra patience and encouragement as he continues to learn to trust the outside world. Pokki has not been neutered, but shows no signs of marking or dominant behavior - in fact, he lets his smaller, neutered foster brother boss him around. Pokki has a heart condition - it is treatable but serious, and needs surgery to fix a blocked valve. Pokki would make a wonderful pet in a low-to-medium active home with a family who adores him as much as he adores them. Sometimes when he's asleep, Pokki starts wagging his tail, and we're pretty sure he's dreaming of his happy future in his new forever home. "

PLEASE NOTE: This animal is not at the Social Tees office all of our dogs and cats are in foster homes while they wait to find their forever families. :) If youd like to apply to adopt this pet, please complete an adoption application at socialteesnyc.org. Because we are a small team and receive hundreds of applications each week, we are unable to respond to every application and every inquiry email, but we do our best. Please have patience! If your application is approved, you will for sure hear from us. If you have questions, please take a look at the Adoption and Fostering FAQs etc. on our website as all common questions are answered there. Thank you for your understanding and flexibility as we work to save these innocent lives!! 

LEARN MORE ABOUT US: socialteesnyc.org; Instagram via @socialteesnyc; Facebook.com/socialteesanimalrescue

animal.description:
Pepita is a sweet little girl who was released from a commerical breeding facility and is loving her new life outside of a cage. She weighs 7 pounds and is 8 years old. Pepita arrived in rescue with a large mammary tumor and severe dental disease. The tumor was removed (and was later found to be malignant) and she had 17 teeth pulled. She is a bit shy, but after she gets comfortable in her surroundings she lets her feisty side come out. She does love to bark, so an apartment would not be a good fit for her. She loves to be held and snuggle up for a nice long nap. She gets along well with the resident dog. She is doing well so far with potty training, but needs to be taken out often. She loves to run and play outside, and does not even mind the snow! 

Pepita has had a couple of bouts of pancreatitis, so the vet has recommended that she be on prescription food to since her tummy is a little sensative. 


	The requirements for Pepita: No exceptions. 
	A fenced in yard is a must. She does not understand the leash at all. 
	Due to Pepita's small size, we believe a home without small children would be best for her. 


The pathology report indicated that the mammary tumor that was removed was malignant. We do not know what the future holds for Pepita, but we are hopeful that the vet was able to remove all of the cancer and that it won't return. 

Her adoption fee is $250. She is up to date on her shots.

animal.description:
FAST FACTS:
*6 Years Old
*Laid-Back Personality
*Dog Friendly
*Older Children
*Mostly Potty Trained/Crate Trained

BIO:
Couch Queen alert! My name is Gina, and I am a low-energy lady who would love to curl up on the couch with you so we can catch up on our stories. As a lady of leisure, I would prefer a calmer home and would do best with older children if you have kiddos since I prefer a zen atmosphere. I get along with other dogs - mostly I am indifferent to them, though I do enjoy going for walkies with the other doggie in my foster home since she helps me keep some pep in my step. I am mostly potty trained - I do better with frequent breaks outside, but am learning to hold it for longer lengths of time - and am crate trained. When I think about my forever home, I imagine a place with lots of cushy doggie beds and a very comfortable couch so I can love and lounge. Wanna pamper me? Then go ahead and fill out that adoption application today!

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess.

animal.description:
Meet Aroo! She is a 2 year old that was rescued from a meat farm in South Korea. We have partners we work with there that pull these dogs from the worst horrors imaginable before they are set to be on someone's dinner plate.
Many of these dogs start off in horrific puppy mill type facilities on tiny rabbit cage size wire crates in complete filth. If they are not sold at 6 or 8 weeks then they either stay for a couple years to be used to breed more and then are sold off to the meat trade, or they are sold off right away. South Korea is one of the only countries that actually farms dogs for their meat. Little dogs are used for elixirs and potions.
Aroo and several of her friends have been flown here for a chance at a future and a real life. Our adoption fee is $600 which helps offset some of the flight costs. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an online application form at https://form.jotform.com/oscarlucy/dog-adoption-app

animal.description: Hiya everyone; meet the active Arvy (pronounced RV)! Arvy is a 1.5 year old Red Heeler X Pug mix and weighs approximately 30-35 lbs. Arvy came to us as an owner surrender along with his daughter Willow (who has already been adopted) and another litter of puppies that he had fathered (who have gone on transport to another rescue group through ARATT). All of the dogs were living outdoors on tethers and are thoroughly enjoying the central heat/air in the rescue housing! Arvy is finally neutered and is now ready for his forever home! He is still working the excess hormones out of his system (this can take a couple months) and wants to mark when outside smelling around. He has mastered the dog doors in our rescue housing and lets himself out to potty now whenever he pleases. Arvy gets along with some dogs (not all), he is a dominant boy and does best with dogs that do not challenge him. He is a very high energy boy and some other dogs do not appreciate his constant "play mode." He loves toys of all kinds, but squeaky toys are his favorite! Arvy is too high energy and is a little too interested in cats, so we believe he would do best in a home without feline friends. He also likes children, especially older kids that are able to play with him (he will jump up on little ones and could accidentally knock them down). Arvy is a great car rider and usually rides crated, however he will free ride well once he calms down. If you are looking for an active partner for long walks, jogs, and adventures; look no further than Arvy!

Available for adoption in New England/East Coast: meet ROSIE!

We are helping with a request to rehome Rosie. She is about four years old and weighs 55lbs.

Rosie is a sweet, loving, active girl.  She loves to run more than anything and loves to be taken on daily 2-3 mile walks. 

She also loves being outside and needs to be in a home that has ample outside yard space for her to play in.

Rosie needs to be in a home with adults and or adults or older teens as she startles easily and does not do well with the hustle and bustle and unpredictability of younger children.

Rosie does fine with adults, sometimes loving to curl up with her favorite person, and sometimes preferring to sit quietly on her own.
Rosie does okay with other dogs but likes to be the boss. She likes to protect her space and family members. We don’t know how she is with cats.

Rosie will go in a crate, but because she does not chew and is not destructive, was not in a crate in her previous home.  She had the run of the house and loves to snooze on the couch.

Rosie’s ideal home would be to a person or couple that does not have young kids or grandkids around and like to be outside and active. 

She is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and housebroken.

If you are interested in adopting, please go to www.luckylabrescue.com and complete an adoption application.

animal.description:
Did somebody say... TENNIS BALL???

Kipper hopes you did, because that means it's time to PLAY! Playtime is Kipper's favorite time, if you couldn't tell by the excitement clear on his face, and he just knows his forever family is reading this pet bio right now and getting ready to go to the store to buy a pack of tennis balls. 

Kipper recently came to THS from another shelter, and since being here we've all come to love him! How could we not, when Kipper is a big goofball who loves nothing more than to run around and play (have we mentioned how much he loves tennis balls yet, or no?) However, at the end of the day, all Kipper wants is a lap to lay his head on, and a new forever family to scratch his nose and ears.

Kipper can be a rough player and will need a family that can help manage his play behavior. He can be jumpy/mouthy and will need an adopter who is willing to train him and teach him appropriate manners. Because he doesn't know his own size, he should not go to a home with young/small children. Kipper cannot go to a home with any cats and should meet any resident dogs before being adopted! Kipper also plays rough and inappropriate with other dogs, and many dogs do not enjoy his play behavior. 

Kipper went to a home for the holidays and the family he stayed with had so much fun with him! His foster mom said he was also very good about pottying outside and let them know when he wanted to go out and never had an accident. If you'd like to see some of his adventures in action, follow this link from his foster family!

https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1-JRsl2wTUYcebvwSDMTRNFXkIwqZp2ZA

Kipper is back in foster while he waits to be adopted, and so he can work on those manners! If you are interested in adopting Kipper, please email foste@toledohumane.org!

If you're interested in adopting Duke, please complete our adoption application on our website at www.bloodhoundrescue.ca Our adoption process and fee are also listed under the application link

Meet Duke!

Duke is an adorable 14 month old bundle of energetic puppy playfulness!  Fun fun fun is on his adjenda so he'd do really well with another dog to play with. Duke is good with children but can easily knock small children over and can be a handful himself. He would do well with taking a basic training class like every puppy should. 

Duke came into rescue with a heart murmur and has had his consultation and echo cardiogram with a cardiologist at the Oakland Veterinary Referal Services in Michigan. He has been diagnosed with a grade V/VI systolic murmur over the left and right thorax and the great news is that Duke doesn't currently require any medication and his activity doesn't need to be monitored. Duke's cardiologist doesn't feel that he'll need any type of heart surgery or heart procedure in the future. He might need to go on a diaretic at some point in his life but they don't feel that he'll need other heart medications. Duke will need to be rechecked by a cardiologist in 9 months to 1 year.

animal.description:
Available for adoption in Texas: Stunning SOFIA!

Sofia is about six-years-old and weighs about 70 pounds. 

Sofia had a difficult start to life. She was lost as a six-month-old puppy, and she was found over six years later! Can you imagine? Her original owners were unable to take her back when Lucky Lab tracked them down. She obviously had been used for breeding in the last six years, and life turned out very different for her than it should have.
Sofia needs an experienced dog owner with patience, who can give her time to decompress, and learn what’s to be expected in her home. She desires a lot of human attention and we think she would do best in a home where her person is with her often.

Sofia is as playful as a young adult dog, romping, and wrestling with her four-legged foster sibling is a lot of fun! She asserted herself as the top dog in her foster home when she arrived, so she may have some alpha tendencies.

Sofia doesn’t seem to know the word “sit,” but she instinctively knows to sit when she approaches someone or they approach her. If she doesn’t get pet fast enough though, she'll paw at them to let them know they need to hurry it up! And belly rubs…ohhh belly rubs!! This is the key to her heart. Sofia much prefers to roll over immediately for a belly rub, as opposed to getting a pet on the head. Belly rubs are life for this girl!

Sofia has come a long way with crate training. She is now fully crate trained and enjoys having that space of her own! In the evenings, especially, she often just goes into her crate to take a nap. She is crated when no one is home, as well as, overnight.

Sofia is house trained but may have an occasional accident if it's raining, as she is not of fan of going outside when her princess paws may get wet (much like her foster sibling – silly girls!). Sofia has also exhibited some minor storm anxiety in her foster home. She's not really a fan of the car, so she'd do best in a home where someone is content with a doggy in the home and isn't hoping for a ride-along buddy.

Sofia has grown very fond of the toy box and has her favorites...namely giant rope toys, and nylabones! She also loves food and gets very excited for meal-time. She is best fed with a slow-feeder bowl so she doesn't inhale her kibble, and bonus - she gets in a little mental stimulation at the same time!

Sofia loves and craves attention, but doesn’t always know how to ask for it correctly, so a patient adopter will be key to her success. She has also been known to be pretty vocal, and she tries to use whining to get her way. As she decompresses and settles into a home, we believe this may improve.

We suspect Sofia never met a leash before she came into Lucky Lab, so she could use a lot of assistance in that area if leash walking is a desired skill. Her 70 lb self is super strong and has been known to pull her foster mom around. For the most part in her foster home, she currently just enjoys backyard time!

Sofia is spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped, and she’s ready for her furever home.

If you think you could provide the perfect home for this gal, please go to www.luckylabrescue.com and complete an adoption application.

animal.description:
Bellagio (Gio) is a dog’s dog. Loves hanging his head out the car window. Good at fetch. Loves walks and playing with other dogs. Howls along with sirens. Wants that squirrel so bad!

A 5-year-old German Shepherd mix, Bellagio is as handsome as they come. He’s friendly, goofy, and loves all the attention he can get. He likes a good ear scratching and will give kisses as payment.

At 82 pounds, Bellagio is a strong guy, but he walks well on leash. He’s doing well on a schedule of 2-3 walks a day. He’s housebroken. As for crates…well, he’s a master demolisher and will need the heavy-duty kind.

If you’re looking for a smart, handsome boy who will be endlessly loyal, consider Bellagio. He is destined to be someone’s devoted companion.

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. Come to the show to find out if this dog is the right fit for you — it's helpful to bring all family members and current dogs. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

You know what you'll find if you look up "charming" in the dictionary? A picture of this blue-eyed beauty. This pup wows every person he meets, and here's why: 

* He's a great communicator. This deaf dog knows lots of hand signals. Sit, stay, down - he's happy to follow your direction (especially if you have a treat, a stick, or a walk to offer). 

* He's an amazing entertainer. Have you ever seen a dog sneak up on a stick, twirl it, roll on it, and then throw it at your feet? Or have you seen a dog jump around and munch on bubbles for 20 minutes at a time? It's quite the show. 

* He's housetrained, non-destructive, and always up for a round of fetch. 

* Did we mention he likes sticks? 

Okay, okay, now before you get in line to meet with this flirt of a dog, let us tell you what Mr. Juke is looking for in his forever home:

Juke is attentive to his handler so he's fine living in a neighborhood where kids hang out, but he'd be most comfortable in a home with only adults and older teenagers.

Hello Earthlings! My name is Marvin the Martian, yup, just like your favorite Looney Tunes character! I am definitely out of this world, but I am no villain! I am here to show all of you humans that extraterrestrials are actually the most loving creatures you will ever come by <3 

Because my heart is so big, I am always overflowing with SO MUCH TO SAY! I'm a pretty little guy, but I've got a big voice! Don't worry, I know how to be quiet too... I just.. sometimes get a little nervous about being left alone.. So if you're a family that spends a good amount of time at home and you can spend some time helping me learn how to be brave on my own, I'm probably your perfect babe! Although I am small, compact and only 15 pounds, I am not suited for any apartment living. I will need a big enough Earth-ship with a yard and enough distance from your neighbors to accommodate this big personality. 

I'm pretty picky with other dogs, but not with my people! I love to love and to be loved. Not to toot my own horn or anything, but I did win the BEST CUDDLER award of 2021 ;) I cannot wait to meet the family that is going to rock my world and FINALLY give me my forever home. 

I can't wait to meet you! If you'd like to meet me, contact my friends at Lost Our Home by putting in a application with MY name on it!


All dog adoptions include the following:
--Spay/neuter surgery
--All current vaccinations
--Microchip with free chip registration
--Free wellness exam through VCA Animal Hospitals
--Access to our Behavior Helpline for the lifetime of the pet
 
For more information or to schedule an appointment to meet this pet, please complete a Dog Adoption Questionnaire online. You can also email us at adoptions@lostourhome.org.

animal.description:
Why hello there, Brahms is the name. Yes, like the German composer Johannes Brahms. Foster mom says I got the name because my first night with Merit, “Rhapsody In E Flat” was what helped me settle down and relax. I may not be able to see but that surely doesn’t slow me down. It may take a bit of bumping into things to figure out my way around…but don’t worry, it doesn’t bother me one bit! Foster mom says I don’t actually know that I’m a big dog and she’s right! I try to fit in all the tiny places. I love taking in all the smells and sounds in new surroundings. There is so much to explore with my nose. I’ve heard the term “Senior” tossed around to describe me but I firmly believe age is just a number and I’m just full of wisdom. I love getting attention from my humans and would love to have a patient home to work with me. Well, Symphony No. 1 just came on so I’m going to go now. Stay tuned for more updates as I continue to learn my new surroundings. If you think we’d be great together, reach out to the people at Merit and they can certainly help you!

Please fill out an adoption application here: https://www.meritpitbullfoundation.com/adoption-form

Our adoption fee is $250.

*All dogs receive the following prior to adoption: Distemper/Parvo Vaccine, Rabies Vaccination, Heartworm Test & Treatment (if needed) Spay/Neuter (no dog will ever be adopted out without being altered), and Microchip. *Puppies too young for rabies or final boosters will need to be vaccinated post-adoption at the expense of the adopter.
*All adopters must be at least 21 years of age.
*We will only place dogs with indoor ONLY homes.
*A home visit and application are required prior to adoption.
*We do check home owners insurance or with your landlord to ensure pit bull type dogs are accepted in your home or apartment.

IMPORTANT: Many homeowner's insurance companies have breed blacklists or "dangerous dogs" lists which include, but are not limited to, pit bulls, American Pit Bull Terriers, American Staffordshire Terriers, Staffordshire Bull Terriers, Rottweilers, Dobermans, Akitas, American Bulldogs, Chows and wolf-hybrids and WILL NOT insure you if they reside in your home or may cancel your insurance if you add a dog of these breeds to your home. If you rent, landlords may also have these same breed restrictions due to their insurance policies. Please check your homeowner's insurance policy or ask your landlord regarding breed discrimination before submitting this application to adopt a pit bull type dog.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Garland
DOB: 11/27/2018
Weight: 42 Pounds
Adoption Fee: $375

Judy Garland is the happiest little pittie mix you've ever seen. We don't know much about her background, but she came up to Minnesota from an overrun shelter in Laredo TX. She may have already had puppies at some point, which is amazing, because she still acts like such a puppy herself. She hasn't let anything get her down. She takes what life gives her with a bounce and a wag. She brightens our home with her love for life and happy energy. Judy has an intensity that comes through in her fierce love, and her play style - best described as wild abandon. But she needs your love too, and will crawl up on your lap and kiss your face until you can't take it anymore, and then fall into a peaceful sleep, snoring away. Her love and trust for people around her, after the uncertainty in her life is nothing short of incredible.

When you get up, she jumps up, ready for anything - "what's our next adventure? I can't wait!" She's curious about everything, and investigates anything new with courage and persistence. She loves her toys and bones and will entertain herself when there's no one around to try to coax into playing with her. When she finds a toy she likes, she positively prances with it over to her bed to give it all her attention. She plays hard with the Resident dogs, and holds her own, even though she's only half their size. But they are fuddy duddies and don't always appreciate being leapt on with such a lack of restraint. They are patient though, and are good sports. Sometimes playing with the big dogs is just so much fun, that she can't contain her excitement and needs a little help to disengage and take a little break. She's always responsive to this guidance and grateful to get a little rest on her own.

Judy thinks little critters are pretty special and can think of nothing better than getting her paws around one of their little necks. That is, she has a high prey drive. The cat in the house has been banished to the basement when Judy is around, as he probably wouldn't be safe in her presence. She's very distracted by squirrels in the yard, and obsessed with the Cat through the baby gate.

She does really well playing with toys, and even chewing on bones with the Resident dogs, but you know how it is: sometimes there's that one special brand new something, and you just don't want it to be with anyone but you. So if one of the Resident dogs gets in her space when she has something super fantastic she has to let them know they've crossed the line. That is, she does some resource guarding. Any new bones, or high value treats or food are given in her crate or a separate room, and that keeps everyone safe and happy. She's more than happy to share with her foster mama and trusts her to only do what's best for her.

She walks on a leash, but will pull if there is something she wants to get after - squirrels, or other dogs she wants to play with or even an intriguing smell. We are working on that and a harness is helping tremendously. Potty training is going really well - she seems to signal by whining and pawing, but we are always working to understand her cues better.

She isn't in a crate for long periods during the day, but she does go in her crate easily for a few treats. She may whine a little at first, but settles down quickly and sleeps the hours away. She also sleeps through the night in a crate next to her foster mom's bed. It's always nice to have something to distract if she'll be left alone - a frozen kong or bone does the trick. She also does well if contained in a room on her own. If given the run of the house when left alone, she would probably get into trouble. Because of her curious nature, it's best to keep chewable items readily available, to deter her from the non-chewable items that might be lying around.

Judy is a fantastic combination of sweet and sassy. She will wiggle her way into your heart and never leave. She plays hard, and she loves even harder. She will LOVE to have her own place to rule the roost, and her own people to love and snuggle with to her heart's content.

There's no place like home.

All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs). Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept. Meet Copper! He's a 7 year old coonhound mix with a gentle demeanor and an old soul. Copper probably toes the line between a medium & large sized pup weighing in at about 55 lbs. He's a very handsome dude with velvety soft fur, long floppy ears and soulful brown eyes. Copper loves walks & does okay on a lease, expert at fetch when he gets the itch and is low/med energy.

Cooper is housebroken, quiet (mostly) and can be left out of his crate unsupervised. He's been the only dog in his household for several years. Copper has been a SAAP dog since I was a puppy and got adopted - but I had to be returned based on interactions with a toddler in the household & would do best in a home without small children. Also, no cats please.

Copper is a bit of a Nervous Nellie meeting strangers - no aggression, just timid. He'll need an adopter that can look past first impressions when they meet based on this shyness. Cooper truly is a lovable guy and a wonderful companion, he just needs a little bit of time to warm up.

The best type of home for Rex needs to meet the following objectives: 
- An adult-only home - no kids.

- Since he has been owned by only one family, he needs a new owner who is patient, thus allowing Rex to take the time he needs in order to adjust to a new home and new people.

Please APPLY to meet Rocky.
Apply at http://caninehumane.org/adoption-application/

Rocky needs an experienced dog owner who is willing to work with him and earn his trust. Once that happens he will be the most amazing and loyal friend. He would do best in a house with a fenced in yard where he can run and play ball. 

Rocky needs a home who is willing to work with a positive reinforcement trainer- he gets nippy at time (probably the cattle dog in him) and can be pretty persistent. Until this behavior is taken care of he is looking for a home without kids! With a consistent routine and direction this behavior should subside quickly. Our trainer is happy to work with anyone interested in getting to know Rocky. This poor boy deserves his forever home. 

He is house trained, crate trained, and very food motivated making him a good candidate for training!  

On walks, he is great when encountering people and walking past other dogs, even if they’re barking at him. He does pull when he sees a particularly enticing squirrel (not all squirrels) but can be redirected. He has no interest in chasing anything else like birds. He is happy to calmly walk up and greet people on walks too!

Adoption Fee is $150
He is up to date on vaccines and has had a wellness exam, heartworm tested and micro-chipped.

 In order to meet any of our dogs, please fill out an application. To fill out an application 
go to http://caninehumane.org/adoption-application/ 

IF THE DOG IS ON PETFINDER THEN IT IS STILL AVAILABLE

www.caninehumane.org 

***BE SURE TO CHECK YOUR SPAM/PROMOTION EMAIL FOLDER FOR CHN RESPONSE TO YOUR APPLICATION***

animal.description: Hi!  My name is Gus and I am a 7 month old border collie mix.  I was born with a condition known as cerebellar hypoplasia.  Basically it means the part of my brain that controls fine motor skills and muscle coordination didn't form fully.  As a result I run and walk a little wonky-- I kind of hop like a bunny.  But, don't let my funny bunny hop prevent you from adopting me.  I am a happy-go -lucky little dude who loves life and adores toys (especially rope toys!  Tug is my FAVORITE game and I'm really good at it!).   I love to play with other dogs and really hope that my furever home has at least one other doggy brother or sister for me.   A home with kids would be cool too.  Once I have warn myself out running and playing,  I really like snuggling with my person on the couch.   I am house-broken, crate-trained and up-to-date on my vaccinations. Because of my condition, it is recommended that I wait until 1 yr to be neutered. But, I will come with a voucher from Herding Haven to get that done once I am old enough.  If you are interested in meeting me please contact kathie@herdinghaven.org

animal.description:
Freddy is about 4 years old, under 50lbs, neutered, and healthy!!! 

He's currently in Puerto Rico but can be flown to the Northeast US. Despite the trauma he's endured, he's energetic and playful! The only signs of the hardship he's faced in his life are his need for a little extra patience while he learns how to be a dog again and an adorable little wobble in his step.

Freddy doesn't need a perfect person. He's just looking for someone to give him a safe and loving home where he can be his aloof, puppy-like self and do what he does best: love his life. He's a sweet boy who desperately deserves a best buddy for life! ?

If you're interested in adopting Freddy, please fill out an application at bit.ly/PSDAdopt

Know someone who looking to welcome an amazing dog into their life? Let them know about Freddy! 

HIT BY A CAR AND LEFT TO DIE! 
.
It's a miracle that we get to say these words:
.
?? Will you adopt Freddy? ??
.
.
Freddy's rescue journey started in March 2020 when we got awful news about a dog in the streets of Puerto Rico. 
.
There's a dog that's been been hit by a car.
He's bleeding and motionless in the street.
Our vet has agreed to open the clinic just for him.
We've given him a name: Freddy.
.
Freddy is in agonizing pain.
Freddy's spine is fractured.
Freddy's back legs are paralyzed.
Freddy's front leg is severely broken.
Freddy is positive for heartworm.
Freddy isn't likely to survive. 
.
But Freddy had our hearts and we were all in. We didn't expect him to survive. We didn't expect him to walk. We didn't expect to share the miraculous news that we get to share with you today.
.
Freddy survived the night.
Freddy survived the week!
Freddy's surgery was successful!
Freddy's legs might work again!
Freddy can WALK!
Freddy is done with heartworm treatment!
Freddy is being discharged from the vet!
.
Finally, the words we fought so hard for but never imagined we'd actually be able to say:
.
Freddy is healthy and ready to find his forever home! 

If they are listed on PetFinder, they have not yet been adopted. If you wish to meet them or find out more about them that is not included in their profile, please fill out our adoption application at http://bit.ly/PSDAdopt and our adoption counselor will contact you as soon as possible.

animal.description:
Our sweet Journey has definitely earned her name! This 2 year old beauty has been through the wringer it seems in her short time spent with us. Journey arrived in our care as a stray and was very skinny, covered in fleas, and sadly pregnant. She quickly won over the heart of one of our staff members who opened up her home to this wiggly, happy girl. Her foster mom got her back on track with nutrition and helped her prepare to be a mother. Journey did deliver her puppies and unfortunately all were stillborn. It was incredibly heartbreaking for both Journey and her foster family. After a vet visit it was determined that Journey has a heart condition called Cardiomyopathy. She does not require medication for this, but her lifespan is unknown with her condition. Despite her physical heart difficulties, Journey is the biggest lover. She lives for attention and wants to be with her people as much as possible. She gets along well with other calm, cool dog friends and prefers a home without kitties. Since Journey was was so skinny and malnourished when she arrived in our care, she does have some issues with food and resource guarding. She will require being fed separately in a crate and needs a home without small children. Her foster mom reports she is crate and house trained and knows quite a few commands. Some of her favorite activities involve playing with toys and cuddling up with you on the couch. We know this special girl deserves a chance at forever, are you the perfect match?

If you're interested in meeting or adopting Journey, please complete an application at: inapl.org/adoption-application. Once it's processed, a member of our team will be in touch with you to schedule a meet and greet appointment. This is the time when you and all members of your household will come to our shelter to officially make your connection with Journey.

Journey
American Bulldog/Boxer mix
Female
DOB: 11/2/2018
Weight: 69.4 lbs.
Heartworm Negative

animal.description:
Meet Melo! Those ears right!?
Melo is a fun-loving, VERY ENERGETIC shepherd mix who loves everyone and everything around him! What's his favorite thing? BELLY RUBS. This goofy guy will walk up to anyone, flop onto his back, and wait for some belly rubbin. Melo needs an experienced owner with a very active lifestyle or with the time to commit to burning off this boy's energy! He needs clear boundaries as he is still a pup, and a smart and high energy one at that! He enjoys hanging out in the front yard outside in the sun and sniffing around. He is good with doggos and doesn't meet a stranger! 

He is very obedient and a fast learner...treats help :) It seems like every day he is mastering a new trick or command! Melo is a strong dog who needs a stronger handler to continue his training! No small kids or cats for this busy boy. He needs someone to keep him engaged through training; he'd be great as a working dog! 

He will be your most loyal companion! Meet Melo today!

Pua is a 3 year old American  Foxhound.  She would be best on acreage as she LOVES to run. She is super intelligent and a problem solver as in” I want to go outside” she will open the door and take off which does make her an escape artist. She is very sweet and loves to cuddle. She is a barker and will let you know if anything ( 4 or two legged) is near!  Pua has no health issues. No aggression issues, loves people, loves other dogs. She can be hyper when someone new comes over to the house. She has tons of energy. Housebroken, can be a counter surfer if she smells something that she wants. Pua does get extremely car sick.  A fenced in home would be best for Pua.

Adoption fee is $425

If you do not hear from us within 7 days please email passion4petsrescue@gmail.com

animal.description:
Meet ODIE! He is a gorgeous SWEETHEART that needs training! More details below.

**During the current health situation**

If you are interested in ADOPTING from the EDISON ANIMAL SHELTER, please email the shelter manager, Becky Snyder at rsnyder@edisonnj.org and she will send you an application to fill out and discuss potentially setting up a meeting. The subject of the email should be "Adoption - Pet's Name". Thank you. Be safe and stay healthy.

ADOPT ME!  Say hello to ODIE. He is a gorgeous SWEETHEART who is probably under one year old. He is happy-go-lucky, fun and very, very energetic. He is bright-eyed and playful. 

Odie needs a home with a fenced yard and someone willing to take the time to give him the attention and training he so desperately needs. He is not the dog for you if you live in an apartment or condo without a yard that he can run in. 

That being said, he really does love to be with people, so just putting him out in a yard alone will not work. He will just sit and wait for you to also come out and play with him. 

With the training he needs, it may be best if he is the only dog in the home. But, if you do have another dog, it would have to be a dog that he can roughhouse with. He enjoys playing with other dogs that are his size and strength.

All of our shelter dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, microchipped and up to date on their vaccinations prior to adoption. 

For our shelter updates, check out Friends of the Edison Animal Shelter Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/edisonanimalshelter

animal.description:
Hi!! My name is Scooby and I am an 11 month old Catahoula Cur Mix who weighs approximately 40 lbs. I still need to put on some more weight and to fill out. Before I was rescued, I spent my days wandering the streets trying to get food and love from wherever I could find some. I saw my foster dad walking his dog and thought “hey he looks really nice” so I followed him home and right inside. I have been fully vaccinated, house trained and know how to walk on a leash. I even know my "sit" command!

My foster mom says I have a sweet personality!! I am a little scared of other dogs because I had to fend for myself for so long, but I’m not food aggressive. I love playing with toys and going for jogs.  When I’m done playing, I love to curl up on my foster mom to cuddle. However, I do need to get my proper exercise and would love an active human who enjoys lots of walks, hikes and even runs. I see every fence as a chance to show how tall I can jump, so my foster mom supervises me when outdoors. I do have separation anxiety and would love to find an owner who works from home or has time to shower me with love. I also enjoy looking out the window and watching people walk by.  At night, I love cuddling up on my fuzzy blanket to fall asleep. I am ready for a forever home and I hope it will be with you!! I would do best in a home with older teens and where all humans in the home have a role in my care. A meet and greet with another dog would be best. Below is a description of my breed.

The Catahoula Leopard Dog is a medium-large, short-coated dog, known for its many varied coat and eye colors and patterns. The word catahoula is of Choctaw origin and is translated to mean “sacred lake.” Catahoulas are the only breed of dog to have historically originated in the state of Louisiana. The breed requires firm guidance and early socialization, as they can be independent, territorial, and protective. For the same reasons, they do not allow mistreatment and will assert themselves in self-defense. Once they know their place in the family unit, they are affectionate, loyal, and gentle. Also called the Catahoula Hog Dog, they are used as stock dogs, bay dogs, tree dogs, watchdogs, guard dogs, and of course as loyal companions. 

Adoption fees details: 
Puppies - Adults $ 550, Seniors $375. These adoption rates include transport from Alexandria, Louisiana to designated New England adopter pick up locations and NE foster homes using either Rescue Road Trips, Pets LLC or CAFA Transport. If you do a search you will see that this is a very reasonable adoption fee and comparable to other rescues. Adoption fee breakdown:Adoption Fee:   $  365.00Transportation Fee:  $ 185.00MA and NH only--Quarantine fee if applicable:  $125.00

Medical details:
All our dogs are altered (spayed or neutered), DHLPP, rabies, Bordetella, Heartworm tested with negative test results, microchipped, treated for parasites and on monthly heartworm and flea and tick prevention. A health certificate is issued by a licensed Louisiana veterinarian.

Adoption details:  
In some instances, a meet and greet is not possible before adoption unless we have a foster home in New England available. Available for a Meeting confirms the dog is in a NE Foster home and available for a meeting in the city state provided.  Most times our dogs get adopted before a foster home becomes available - and if so, they go straight to adopters home. Foster parents talk to adopters and feel confident that this will be a match before our dogs are transported up. Also if by some chance it is not a match we have a safety net in place as we ask that adopters to let us know that it is not a match and we direct you to take the dog to a foster home or boarding kennel once that is arranged. If necessary, we will ask you to foster the dog until a foster home can be arranged. 
Transport details:Rescue Road Trips (rescueroadtrips.com), Pets LLC (petsllc.net) or CAFA Transport will deliver our precious pups on commercial rescue animal transport to designated locations.  The fee is 185.00 which IS INCLUDED in your adoption fee already.**Rescue Road Trips, was featured on The Today Show - view it at http://www.today.com/video/today/55034556#55034556

MA and NH RESIDENTS:
If you are a Massachusetts or New Hampshire residence, an additional fee of $125.00 will apply due to State quarantine fee requirements. If the dog is in a foster home in MA or NH, this fee will be added in the adoption fee regardless of where the adopters home is located making the total adoption fee $675.00 for puppies and adults $500.00 for Seniors, otherwise the full adoption fee for all other states is $550.00 for puppies and adults and $375.00 for seniors. This includes a 48 quarantine, recheck by a MA licensed veterinarian, and issued a MA health certificate.

Visit all our available dogs at www.cenlaallianceforanimals.comWe update and add dogs frequently.

We hope to help make a difference in a rescue dogs life into loving responsible homes.

animal.description:
Hi there - nice to meet you!  My name is STYX!   I am 4-5 months old and weigh in at 35 lbs. I still have some growing to do, but should stay in the medium size range.  I’m a pit bull mix and my foster mom says the brown specks on my ears and nose make me super cute.    

I was on a road wandering with another puppy when when a kind rescue lady pulled up with her van.  We were hungry and scared so we jumped right in because we knew we that life would get better from there....and it did!   For a while, I was sick with with Parvo - that’s a bad puppy illness - but with good vet care and lots of TLC from my fosters, I got all better and am now a healthy, happy pup ready for my new home in the New Year!

An important thing you should know about me is that I am hearing impaired.  Some might call it a disability, but It is normal for me cuz’ it’s what I have always known!   If my new family can give me some special training with hand signals, I know I’ll become the best dog ever!  Everyone tells me that deaf dogs live happy lives and bond well with their humans and I cannot wait to meet my special new family!  If they have had experience with a dog that with a disability, that would be perfect!   

My foster mom says I am a very sweet boy.  I really do love my people!  I'm still young and have plenty of puppy mischief in me, but some training will help me to learn all my manners!   I get along well with the dogs in my foster home. Sometimes I can be a little protective of my food around other dogs  (not humans) so just something to know if another dog is in my new home.  I like kids a lot and enjoyed meeting the older children that came to visit.   My rescue thinks my best home will be an adult/teen one because my puppy playfulness may be a little much for young children.  Older kids could also help with my training and understand my unique needs!  My foster mom says a reline free home would probably be best for me!  I am learning the ropes of house and crate training and my new family can help me finish that up.  A consistent routine and positive reinforcement will help us get it down pretty quick! I love my people and sometimes get a little barky when we are separated - so I would love a home where folks are not gone all day. 

I have been neutered and am up to date on my vaccines. I am also micro-chipped and on flea-tick and heartworm preventative.  If you love pitties and have the time and experience for a pup like me, I know we’ll be great pals.  I have years of loyalty and devotion to give you.   Please email Chris at rescue3@earthlink.net  and she will zip an application out to you!  My adoption fee is $350.

Like us on Facebook at www. facebook.com/pawsclawsnewengland
Follow/tag us on Instagram: @pawsclawsne or #pawsclawsne

animal.description: Hello, everyone! My name's Whiskey, but my foster thinks I should've been named after the Energizer Bunny. I'm a sweet, rambunctious boy who loves to play fetch, as well as tug-of-war. I need a home that'll give me an outlet for all my energy! I can play all day at daycare, take a half hour nap, then am ready to race and wrestle with my dog foster siblings until I wear them out and have to go to the humans to throw the ball. I'd be perfect to get into doggy sports, like dock diving or fly ball; I'd also make an excellent running partner! I get along well with all my doggo foster brothers and sisters (who are my size and larger). I'm not a fan of those kitty things, though. I go in my kennel to eat my meals, and like to sleep with my "big" dog siblings all night. I am also looking for a comfy couch, and would like to rest my head on your lap. If you're energetic and want a fun guy to hang out with, please, fill out an application so we can meet, and let the fun begin! ...

animal.description:
Meet Atti:

Atti is a ~1.5 yr old, neutered male Anatolian Shepherd mix believed to be a farm dog when he lived in Iran. While aspects of Atti's looks tell a story of trauma - his temperament reflects anything but.  For a boy who had never lived inside a home or had people treat him well, he's quickly adjusted to living in a whole new world like a rock star.

This incredibly regal boy is stoic, friendly, calm, gentle, quick to bond, and even quicker to steal hearts with his casual and understated offer of "paw" when you least expect it. He's a great communicator and will go get his leash for you if you forget it's time to go for a walk.  Forget to put his bed outside?  He'll grab a towel and take it outside so he has a comfy spot to lay in the sun and watch over his kingdom.  He instinctively knew that the bathroom belongs outside, and has never had an accident in the house.

He enjoys the company of other dogs, understands and wholly embraces the couch potato concept and is a very pleasant walking companion (Atti needs only a moderate level of exercise as a former leg injury precludes him from long hikes and runs). Atti enjoys children and looks forward to the supplemental care he receives from his foster's 11 yr old neighbor.  He's the perfect combination of calm and playful.

Atti's huge hearted rescuer worked with a group of s/hero's to transport him from Iran to the US. He is nearing a clean bill of health (receiving medication for a bladder infection). The ideal home for Atti would be a home with another dog as he and Tucker, his foster's dog, quickly became BFFs and the joy of watching them play is priceless. Any family lucky enough to adopt this boy will be blessed with a special sentient being (NOTE: we love all dogs...and well...this boy is pretty special). Please contact us if you are interested in hearing more about Atti.

HINT: Atti is the large dog with spots on his nose in the pics and videos

Link to video: https://youtu.be/bwg_RPynMzQ

Contacts:
Kit O'Doherty, kitodoherty@gmail.com, (650) 274-5236 c
Chris Guio, cguio1@yahoo.com, (650) 438-0617 c

Shelter staff started a feeding program to safely add weight to his emaciated frame and look at him now!  He’s had quite a journey but he’s now a healthy 45 pounds, loves his toys and especially his blankets and bed.  
River is hoping to find a loving family to call his very own and to start the new year with only good things ahead....including never having to worry about his next meal again. 
He’s a fella with lots of love to give. Please send an email to adoptions@wbrcouncil.org if you are interested in adopting River.

animal.description: Meet Telemachus! Are you his Odysseus? In Greek mythology, Telemachus relentlessly searched for his father, Odysseus, as family meant everything to him. However, when you have four paws, it's really better to let the humans do the searching, so Telemachus is focusing on smaller battles with goals he can obtain! Those have taken place in his structured foster home! Specifically, he has conquered the battle of playing appropriately with his foster (human) mom. He realized treats are delicious, and since he's so smart, he is learning very quickly that using good manners means lots of tasty morsels and positive attention from his human. He has even learned that if he simply sits or shakes he can earn a treat for that as well and performs gladly. Other commands he is eagerly learning are: stay, leave-it and off. Telemachus loves a treat, but he doesn't discriminate and loves doggie chow too. Telemachus longs for his father, but would really enjoy doggie siblings who enjoy a fun romp around the yard! And humans who share his desire for adventure and will invite him along! While he waits and trusts his foster mom to find his father, you better believe he is enjoying relaxing in a soft and cozy doggie bed because he is that perfect combination of playful pup and couch potato. E-mail foster@kcpetproject.org to meet him!
