animal.description:
If this nice boy interests you we ask that you go to www.jcldr.com and put in an application for him first, that gives us a feel for you and yours. The meet and greet is always last and no one is obligated to adopt by putting in an application 

STATS: Coal is an approximately 1.5 years old Catahoula mix.  He is neutered and crate broke. He runs in to his crate as soon as he knows it is time for food and will regularly hang out in there when it is open. He likes to chew on an antler and will play fetch but has a short attention span. Coal is housebroken but has peed in the house a few times when he has been excited (e.g. new visitors).  He is fully vaccinated and is microchipped. Coal weighs approximately 60 pounds.  He is fed Taste of the Wild Pacific Stream (Salmon) twice a day.  Coal does well with nail trims but thinks it is a game and will try to nibble on your hands or the trimmer or pull his feet away so he can paw at you to instigate play; I’ve found he does best with one or two feet at a time, a play break, and then try again. He does well with veterinarian visits as far as I can tell (it is curbside pick-up only here, but I have not heard anything negative). He has thrown up once on a car ride, but it was on twisty, windy mountain roads, so he may not always vomit in the car. Coal has been doing well walking on a leash. We have used a Martingale collar for training, and he is responding well to not pulling while on the leash and heeling beside me while we walk. He is quite mouthy still  and that is typical puppy stuff, he thinks it is always time to play. Coal has not been around children while in foster, but given his playful, rambunctious nature, he may do best with older children (he does not seem to realize his size and I could see him accidentally knocking a small child over). He is a very smart boy and picks up on things quickly; he makes good eye contact and wants to please people and be told he’s a ‘good boy’.  He gets along well with my other 3 dogs (two males and one female). He loves to play and run in the yard, so another dog friend could be great for him. He has not been around cats or small animals while in foster, but he seems interested in the wild turkeys outside the fence (I’m not sure if he’d chase or catch them if left to his own devices).

HISTORY: Coal was picked up by the shelter as a stay, so there is no previous known history.  He has been in foster for about 6 weeks now and has shown himself to be a very well-adjusted boy. He picks up on cues and commands quickly and has figured out the routine of the household. 

GOOD: Coal is a sweet, loyal boy. He loves to cuddle and have his belly rubbed. When I arrive home from work, he is wiggly and bendy coming out of his crate, so excited to see me, greet me and get attention. At bedtime he will jump right on the bed ready for his nightly cuddle before going to sleep. He is a great companion for a hike/walk.  He walks well on a leash but would probably pull if something caught his attention.  He likes to sit on your feet whenever he can and enjoys being (very) near his people. He follows me everywhere like a shadow.  He loves catching ice cubes if they fall on the ground from the automatic dispenser in the refrigerator (if he hears the ice dispenser making noise, he comes running from wherever he is!). He enjoys playing with toys (with me and/or the other dogs) and loves having the freedom to explore around the fenced in yard. He does not bark very often, but he does bark excitedly when there are turkeys in the yard.  He has his moments of being hyper and playful, but then others where he is very mellow and enjoys just sitting on the couch with you. He would do well with another dog or as the only dog. Another dog friend should enjoy playing rough, though, as Coal can get pretty rowdy which is typical of Catahoulas.. Coal is very intelligent and picks up on commands quickly. He is very treat motivated (I use pieces of his dog food as treats), which makes training him fairly easy.  He makes good eye contact and is very, very focused when you ask him to do something. He is a very smart boy and picks up on things quickly. 

BAD: He is mouthy still and will bite and nibble (playfully) when you pet him, which might not be a good fit for younger children until he learns not to do that. 

UGLY: He seems selective about male dog friends when there is a lot going on around him. He once got into a fight with one of my dogs (my dog instigated it because Coal was playing roughly with one of my other dogs). Coal initially did not respond, but he was amped up from playing and when my dog (male) inserted himself into the mix, Coal reacted. Both dogs immediately stopped when squirted with water from a pop-top water bottle, and they have had no issues since. Coal also attacked a smaller male dog; once again, he seemed to be overstimulated and eventually went from being playful to becoming aggressive; he again responded to the pop-top water bottle.when applied properly.

animal.description:
***AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION AT OUR FLORIDA LOCATION***

Emily is a female Heeler mix. She is around 3 years old and weighs approximately 35 lbs. She is very sweet, gentle and loving. She has Heeler energy.  A Heeler/herding dog savvy household would be helpful.

Emily was found down a dirt road living under an abandoned house with her litter of puppies. She was bringing her pups lizards to eat because that’s all she could find.  This girl has not had an easy road but worked hard to raise her babies and keep them safe on her own until we stepped in to help her. As you can see, she is partially blind in one eye due to a cataract, but she doesn't let it hold her back. 

Emily, like so many of our adults and mommas that come in, is heartworm positive. This is NOT contagious and is not a death sentence! We have started her on heartgard which will keep new worms from growing and allow the ones already present to die off slowly. This is the safest way to do it in the group home setting. Included in her adoption is a year supply of Heartgard. 

She is currently living with a foster and is housetrained, travels well in the truck and golf cart, walks well on a leash, and is good mannered.  She is good with other dogs. She is good with kids too, though probably not a good mix with very young children. 

Emily deserves a family to love her and give her all the things she has never had! 

Emily is available in Bonifay, Florida through the rescue efforts of The Lucky Puppy Rescue. The minimum $250 adoption fee includes spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, de-worm, flea prevention, heartworm prevention and martingale safety collar. Adoption fee payment methods accepted are credit, debit, Paypal and bank checks. No personal checks or cash. Applications must be submitted through our website - theluckypuppy.org - thank you! You may copy and paste the following link to apply: http://www.theluckypuppy.org/adoption-application.

animal.description:
***Honey will need a female only, child-free/pet-free home***

***TRANSPORT OF HONEY MUST BE WITHIN 4 HOURS OF WEST HAVEN, CT***

My name is HONEY! I came to LPDR when my owner became sick and went into longterm care. My Forever Home needs to be filled with loving and patient females who are home most of the time and do not have other dogs or cats. I love being on the couch and sleeping in my foster mom's bed. I am too short to get on the bed on my own and I don't like the stairs she got for me, but if I could, I'd stay under the covers all day! I don't really like sweaters so when we go outside I try to be quick. My foster mom has learned that I only like female people and I am protective of my people once I bond with them. No males, and no children in my forever home please. I love chewing on my stuffed animals and playing with my foster mom. I have to bring my toys to bed with me so my new people should have a big bed! I get a little worried when we go in the car but I like when we go to the beach or get a treat at Dunkin. I am house trained, but no crates for me. I enjoy going on walks, but would love a fenced yard!

If you want to know more about me, send an email to foster mom Shelly at shelly.davis579@gmail.com

Honey's Adoption fee is $325. If she is adopted over a state line there will be a $45.00 charge for a health certificate (required by law).

animal.description:
Hey everyone, I’m dandelion! My mom, Honeybee, was a pit Bull mix but we don’t know about my dad. Merit says that is how rescue works most of the time. I’m a very handsome 9 month old pup looking for a good home who will be patient with me. There is this thing called a pandemic going on (I don’t know what that is but I guess it’s a big thing) and I didn’t get to explore a lot of places as a puppy...so new things are hard for me. I warm up eventually to people and to dogs but I’ll need some help and guidance. I know I can be a great family dog because I would do anything for my people.

I’ve got some basic obedience training under my belt and I’m very smart. If you are a family looking for a guy like me then reach out to Merit and we can see if it’s meant to be! 

Please fill out an adoption application here: https://www.meritpitbullfoundation.com/adoption-form

Our adoption fee is $350 for puppies WITH a $100 REFUND with proof of training.

*All dogs receive the following prior to adoption: Distemper/Parvo Vaccine, Rabies Vaccination, Heartworm Test & Treatment (if needed) Spay/Neuter (no dog will ever be adopted out without being altered), and Microchip. *Puppies too young for rabies or final boosters will need to be vaccinated post-adoption at the expense of the adopter.
*All adopters must be at least 21 years of age.
*We will only place dogs with indoor ONLY homes.
*A home visit and application are required prior to adoption.
*We do check home owners insurance or with your landlord to ensure pit bull type dogs are accepted in your home or apartment.

IMPORTANT: Many homeowner's insurance companies have breed blacklists or "dangerous dogs" lists which include, but are not limited to, pit bulls, American Pit Bull Terriers, American Staffordshire Terriers, Staffordshire Bull Terriers, Rottweilers, Dobermans, Akitas, American Bulldogs, Chows and wolf-hybrids and WILL NOT insure you if they reside in your home or may cancel your insurance if you add a dog of these breeds to your home. If you rent, landlords may also have these same breed restrictions due to their insurance policies. Please check your homeowner's insurance policy or ask your landlord regarding breed discrimination before submitting this application to adopt a pit bull type dog.

animal.description:
Breed: Border Collie mix
Sex: Neutered Male
DOB: ~12/15/2019
Weight: 54 lbs
Energy Level: High
Personality Type: Talkative, People-Oriented, Energetic
History: Transferred from another shelter
Good With: Dogs but is a little picky, Kid 8+ years
Fence Requirements: Required!
Ideal Home: Active home! No apartments, please! Please do research on this breed before adopting!
Special Info:

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

Toot is a big Labrador mix boy that was born in December 2016 and weighs 66 pounds. Here is what his handler had to say about him after taking him out on an adventure:


Toot Toot is a jovial "BIG BOY" who is also a very well behaved passenger. No complaints about my driving. I don't think he even licked my windows, he just quietly enjoyed the scenery as we drove up the mountain. He and I sat and looked out at a beautiful view of the valley.

Toot is a snuggly "leaner". When he throws his full weight into you, it's best to be sitting down. He knows SIT but usually drops from SIT straight down into a crazy roll which he seriously enjoys. He has a REALLY BIG head and very small ears. I checked to see if they had been cropped but his ears are just SMALL. No judgement. Just an observation. And while I am NOT body shaming him, his tail is not long and it's not short. It's half a tail. All of his physical "quirks" make him that much more handsome. AND HE KNOWS IT!

Toot likes toys. He had his eye on a pink teddy bear and wanted to bring it back to the shelter with him. He is good on a leash, he loves hiking and exploring, and seemed grateful for his day out. Toot is SUCH A GOOD BOY!


We're open Wednesday - Sunday 12 - 5 p.m but are doing meet & greets and adoptions by appointment only.  

The adoption fee is $90 which includes a free veterinary exam within 2 weeks of adoption at local participating vets, up to date vaccinations, heartworm test,  heartworm preventative, dewormer, flea preventative, microchip, & spay or neuter.

animal.description:
Rex is a neutered male shepherd mix. He is about 2 years old. He came to the shelter as a stray, so his history is unknown.

When meeting new people, or seeing strangers, Rex is extremely nervous and anxious. This is referred to as stranger danger. When on a walk, he may pull and jump about. He is difficult to walk, and loses focus easily. When Rex is uncomfortable, it can be challenging to get him back to a calm state. Under stress, Rex is vocal. He reacts the same way to other dogs. In a more comfortable environment, and with people he knows and trusts, he can be his true self and is friendly, playful, and energetic.

Rex wants to learn and is quite intelligent. He is food motivated and has already learned some basic skills. It is required he goes to professional private dog training classes to sharpen up his skills and to help him create a bond with his family. Rex loves to burn his energy by running around and playing with soft-textured toys like ropes and plushies. Rex is looking for a home without any other pets, including dogs, cats, and small animals. He would not enjoy going to a dog park and would not be a candidate for that kind of environment.

Rex's home should have experience owning and working with large breed dogs. They should be active and excited to spend lots of time each day exercising Rex and working on his training. He must be adopted by an adult-only household (18+) without any other pets. A single-dwelling home would be best (no apartments or condos). He is not recommended for first time dog owners.

Rex is eating a special diet called Royal Canin Digestive Diet. This food has helped Rex with his sensitive stomach. He should stay on this diet unless a veterinarian suggests otherwise.

Do you have the perfect home for Rex? Please submit a Dog Adoption Application to the Adoptions department.

https://omhs.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/OMHS-AdoptionApplication-Dog.pdf

You may submit your completed adoption application by placing it in our drop dox to the left of the shelter doors, by emailing it to adoptions@omhs.ca, or by faxing it to 905-845-1973. The adoption application must be submitted for a particular animal.
 Primary Color: Tri Color Weight: 33.2kg Age: 2yrs 0mths 1wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description: Hello, my name is Ky! I am new to the shelter! I was surrendered because my family was no longer able to care for me. My previoius family reports that I do not get along with other animals. I also prefer males more than females. I have never been around children. I have a tendency to guard toys. I can be a nervous dog and should probably go to an experienced home who is willing to give me time to settle in and will be dedicated to my continued training. Please keep checking my profile for updates as the staff gets to know me better! If this dog has been successful in our play groups it is not a guarantee that a dog will be social with other dogs in their home or in public settings. Dogs are individuals and have personality conflicts, just like us. Play groups do not guarantee that territorial or resource guarding issues will not surface in the home. While play groups do help us get to know the dog's better, once they are adopted their new environments and new relationships will influence their behavior in ways we cannot predict. The Adoption Fee Includes: - initial canine distemper combination vaccination - first worming or stool check - rabies vaccination (for animals over 3 months of age) - AVID microchipping - flea treatment/preventative - spaying or neutering Adoption fee: $135.00 Per state law, ALL ADOPTERS must purchase a non-refundable 2021 dog license at time of adoption for any canine three months and older. The cost of the license is $7.00. (Senior Citizen or Person with Disability-$5.00) Leash and collar included

animal.description:
Meet Piglet! She is a deaf, 9-month old female Stafforshire/ Bulldog/ possibly Chinese Crested mix. She’s super playful and fun. She loves to chase shadows and lasers so it’s very easy to exercise her. A home with experience with deaf dogs would be a huge plus! She’s easily trained and learns a new routine in one day, she just needs some dedication. The best part is she sleeps through any scary sounds dogs tend to have issues with like fireworks and vacuums!!

She does super well with other dogs, meeting them and playing with them — but has not done well living with any dogs longer than about a month so does she need a home where she’ll be an only fur child. 

Older kids are great, no little kids and no cats. Crate trained, leash trained, microchipped, spayed and house broken. 5 classes at Sunny Day Acres where she is being fostered are included in her adoption fee (they love her that much!)

This is a courtesy post on behalf of Sunny Day Acres. The adoption fee is $450. Our team at Big Love will vet and forward all qualified applicants to our partners at Sunny Day. If you’re chosen you will hear from us!

animal.description: Meet the Firecracker Pups! These dazzling Shepherd and possibly Labrador mixes are sure to make your heart burst with their cuteness! They are 2 months old and looking for forever families to have a blast with! Their mama, Firecracker, is a beautiful Shepherd mix who is on the large side at 60 lbs. We aren't sure who dad is so we don't know what all these sweeties are mixed with, but they seem to be on track to be large dogs when full grown. Sparkler is looking for a family that understands the time, patience, and energy needed to raise a young pup. We require all puppy adopters to provide training that includes: house training, basic training, leash training, and socialization. Additionally, this cutie is going to need proper exercise, mental stimulation, and your attention and love to grow up to be the best companion. We do not allow our dogs or puppies to sleep or live outside; they must be incorporated into your family and be made a priority in your life. In return, you will have the most loving and loyal family member you could ask for. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting a puppy, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! Please note that processing time for applications is currently three to four weeks. We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description: Meet Douglas! He is around 9 years young and is an Australian Shepherd mix. He enjoys and asks for attention from people and gets along with other dogs as long as they don't continually get all up in his personal space too much. He would do better with quieter, easygoing dog friends, but does not need a dog companion at home. Douglas knows many basic commands including Sit, Shake & Come. In his current foster home, he also uses the dog door, is completely house trained and walks well on a leash. He is fostered with older children and loves them, but young children might be a bit much for him. Douglas loves a good belly scratch, enjoys a nice stroll around the neighborhood, smelling the Roses each day and is looking for a loving forever family in his later years. animal.description: This mama dog has had a pretty rough life. She's had at least a few litters in her life time and spent quite a while living on her own on the streets. She was eventually spotted running and hiding while holding up one of her back legs and not wanting to use it. Presumably she had been hit by a car, but wouldn't let anyone get close to help. Eventually one of our own volunteers managed to successfully trap her so we could get her the medical attention she needed. We were able to save the leg and treat her heartworm. She's doing much better now and loves the girls at the vet clinic where she received her treatment. She's still wary of strangers, but just needs some time to get to know you. She's very sweet and affectionate once she gets past her initial shyness.
